# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: neurotransmitters
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Acetylcholine is the neurotransmitter used at the neuromuscular junction.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] In other words, it is the chemical that motor neurons of the nervous system release in order to activate muscles.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] This property means that drugs that affect cholinergic systems can have very dangerous effects ranging from paralysis to convulsions.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Acetylcholine is also a neurotransmitter in the autonomic nervous system, both as an internal transmitter for both the sympathetic and the parasympathetic nervous system, and as the final product released by the parasympathetic nervous system.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Acetylcholine is the primary neurotransmitter of the parasympathetic nervous system.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] In the brain, acetylcholine functions as a neurotransmitter and as a neuromodulator.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The brain contains a number of cholinergic areas, each with distinct functions; such as playing an important role in arousal, attention, memory and motivation.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Acetylcholine has also been found in cells of non-neural origins as well as microbes.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Recently, enzymes related to its synthesis, degradation and cellular uptake have been traced back to early origins of unicellular eukaryotes.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The protist pathogens *Acanthamoeba* spp. have shown evidence of the presence of ACh, which provides growth and proliferative signals via a membrane-located M1-muscarinic receptor homolog.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Partly because of acetylcholine's muscle-activating function, but also because of its functions in the autonomic nervous system and brain, many important drugs exert their effects by altering cholinergic transmission.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Numerous venoms and toxins produced by plants, animals, and bacteria, as well as chemical nerve agents such as sarin, cause harm by inactivating or hyperactivating muscles through their influences on the neuromuscular junction.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Drugs that act on muscarinic acetylcholine receptors, such as atropine, can be poisonous in large quantities, but in smaller doses they are commonly used to treat certain heart conditions and eye problems.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Scopolamine, or diphenhydramine, which also act mainly on muscarinic receptors in an inhibitory fashion in the brain (especially the M1 receptor) can cause delirium, hallucinations, and amnesia through receptor antagonism at these sites.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] So far as of 2016, only the M1 receptor subtype has been implicated in anticholinergic delirium.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The addictive qualities of nicotine are derived from its effects on nicotinic acetylcholine receptors in the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Acetylcholine is a choline molecule that has been acetylated at the oxygen atom.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Because of the charged ammonium group, acetylcholine does not penetrate lipid membranes.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Because of this, when the molecule is introduced externally, it remains in the extracellular space and at present it is considered that the molecule does not pass through the blood–brain barrier.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Acetylcholine is synthesized in certain neurons by the enzyme choline acetyltransferase from the compounds choline and acetyl-CoA.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Cholinergic neurons are capable of producing ACh.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] An example of a central cholinergic area is the nucleus basalis of Meynert in the basal forebrain.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The enzyme acetylcholinesterase converts acetylcholine into the inactive metabolites choline and acetate.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] This enzyme is abundant in the synaptic cleft, and its role in rapidly clearing free acetylcholine from the synapse is essential for proper muscle function.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Certain neurotoxins work by inhibiting acetylcholinesterase, thus leading to excess acetylcholine at the neuromuscular junction, causing paralysis of the muscles needed for breathing and stopping the beating of the heart.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Acetylcholine functions in both the central nervous system (CNS) and the peripheral nervous system (PNS).
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] In the CNS, cholinergic projections from the basal forebrain to the cerebral cortex and hippocampus support the cognitive functions of those target areas.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] In the PNS, acetylcholine activates muscles and is a major neurotransmitter in the autonomic nervous system.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Like many other biologically active substances, acetylcholine exerts its effects by binding to and activating receptors located on the surface of cells.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] There are two main classes of acetylcholine receptor, nicotinic and muscarinic.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] They are named for chemicals that can selectively activate each type of receptor without activating the other: muscarine is a compound found in the mushroom *Amanita muscaria*; nicotine is found in tobacco.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Nicotinic acetylcholine receptors are ligand-gated ion channels permeable to sodium, potassium, and calcium ions.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] In other words, they are ion channels embedded in cell membranes, capable of switching from a closed to an open state when acetylcholine binds to them; in the open state they allow ions to pass through.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Nicotinic receptors come in two main types, known as muscle-type and neuronal-type.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The muscle-type can be selectively blocked by curare, the neuronal-type by hexamethonium.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The main location of muscle-type receptors is on muscle cells, as described in more detail below.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Neuronal-type receptors are located in autonomic ganglia (both sympathetic and parasympathetic), and in the central nervous system.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Muscarinic acetylcholine receptors have a more complex mechanism, and affect target cells over a longer time frame.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] In mammals, five subtypes of muscarinic receptors have been identified, labeled M1 through M5.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] All of them function as G protein-coupled receptors, meaning that they exert their effects via a second messenger system.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The M1, M3, and M5 subtypes are Gq-coupled; they increase intracellular levels of IP3 and calcium by activating phospholipase C.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Their effect on target cells is usually excitatory.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The M2 and M4 subtypes are Gi/Go-coupled; they decrease intracellular levels of cAMP by inhibiting adenylate cyclase.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Their effect on target cells is usually inhibitory.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Muscarinic acetylcholine receptors are found in both the central nervous system and the peripheral nervous system of the heart, lungs, upper gastrointestinal tract, and sweat glands.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Acetylcholine is the substance the nervous system uses to activate skeletal muscles, a kind of striated muscle.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] These are the muscles used for all types of voluntary movement, in contrast to smooth muscle tissue, which is involved in a range of involuntary activities such as movement of food through the gastrointestinal tract and constriction of blood vessels.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Skeletal muscles are directly controlled by motor neurons located in the spinal cord or, in a few cases, the brainstem.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] These motor neurons send their axons through motor nerves, from which they emerge to connect to muscle fibers at a special type of synapse called the neuromuscular junction.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] When a motor neuron generates an action potential, it travels rapidly along the nerve until it reaches the neuromuscular junction, where it initiates an electrochemical process that causes acetylcholine to be released into the space between the presynaptic terminal and the muscle fiber.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The acetylcholine molecules then bind to nicotinic ion-channel receptors on the muscle cell membrane, causing the ion channels to open.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Sodium ions then flow into the muscle cell, initiating a sequence of steps that finally produce muscle contraction.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Calcium channel blockers (nifedipine, diltiazem) do not affect P-channels.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] These drugs affect L-type calcium channels.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The autonomic nervous system controls a wide range of involuntary and unconscious body functions.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Its main branches are the sympathetic nervous system and parasympathetic nervous system.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Broadly speaking, the function of the sympathetic nervous system is to mobilize the body for action; the phrase often invoked to describe it is fight-or-flight.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The function of the parasympathetic nervous system is to put the body in a state conducive to rest, regeneration, digestion, and reproduction; the phrase often invoked to describe it is "rest and digest" or "feed and breed".
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Both of these aforementioned systems use acetylcholine, but in different ways.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] At a schematic level, the sympathetic and parasympathetic nervous systems are both organized in essentially the same way: preganglionic neurons in the central nervous system send projections to neurons located in autonomic ganglia, which send output projections to virtually every tissue of the body.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] In both branches the internal connections, the projections from the central nervous system to the autonomic ganglia, use acetylcholine as a neurotransmitter to innervate (or excite) ganglia neurons.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] In the parasympathetic nervous system the output connections, the projections from ganglion neurons to tissues that do not belong to the nervous system, also release acetylcholine but act on muscarinic receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] In the sympathetic nervous system the output connections mainly release noradrenaline, although acetylcholine is released at a few points, such as the sudomotor innervation of the sweat glands.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Acetylcholine in the serum exerts a direct effect on vascular tone by binding to muscarinic receptors present on vascular endothelium.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] These cells respond by increasing production of nitric oxide, which signals the surrounding smooth muscle to relax, leading to vasodilation.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] In the central nervous system, ACh has a variety of effects on plasticity, arousal and reward.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] ACh has an important role in the enhancement of alertness when we wake up, in sustaining attention and in learning and memory.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Damage to the cholinergic (acetylcholine-producing) system in the brain has been shown to be associated with the memory deficits associated with Alzheimer's disease.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] ACh has also been shown to promote REM sleep.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] In the brainstem acetylcholine originates from the Pedunculopontine nucleus and laterodorsal tegmental nucleus collectively known as the mesopontine tegmentum area or pontomesencephalotegmental complex.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] In addition, ACh acts as an important internal transmitter in the striatum, which is part of the basal ganglia.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] It is released by cholinergic interneurons.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] In humans, non-human primates and rodents, these interneurons respond to salient environmental stimuli with responses that are temporally aligned with the responses of dopaminergic neurons of the substantia nigra.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Acetylcholine has been implicated in learning and memory in several ways.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The anticholinergic drug scopolamine impairs acquisition of new information in humans and animals.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Acetylcholine (ACh) has traditionally been seen as vital for learning and memory, but recent studies question its purely positive role.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Too much ACh can interfere with memory consolidation, particularly during sleep, and may worsen verbal memory in early Alzheimer’s disease (AD) and mild cognitive impairment (MCI).
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Excessive activation of ACh pathways can also overstimulate glutamate activity, contributing to AD progression.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Researchers propose that ACh levels first increase and later decrease throughout AD and Parkinson’s disease dementia (PDD), due to initial overstimulation followed by neuron loss.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] They emphasize that cholinesterase inhibitors may not help all cognitive symptoms and could disrupt natural ACh balance, showing that ACh’s effects on memory are complex and require further investigation.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The disease myasthenia gravis, characterized by muscle weakness and fatigue, occurs when the body inappropriately produces antibodies against acetylcholine nicotinic receptors, and thus inhibits proper acetylcholine signal transmission.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Over time, the motor end plate is destroyed.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Drugs that competitively inhibit acetylcholinesterase (e.g., neostigmine, physostigmine, or primarily pyridostigmine) are effective in treating the symptoms of this disorder.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] They allow endogenously released acetylcholine more time to interact with its respective receptor before being inactivated by acetylcholinesterase in the synaptic cleft (the space between nerve and muscle).
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Nerves release ACh at the neuromuscular junction.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] ACh binds to ACh receptors on the muscle surface and causes muscle contraction.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Then the immune system produces autoantibodies that attack or black the ACh receptors on the muscle.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Therefore, the signal from the nerve to the muscle is weakened or lost.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Juvenile MG is more frequently seen in people of Asian and African descent.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Blocking, hindering or mimicking the action of acetylcholine has many uses in medicine.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Drugs acting on the acetylcholine system are either agonists to the receptors, stimulating the system, or antagonists, inhibiting it.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Acetylcholine receptor agonists and antagonists can either have an effect directly on the receptors or exert their effects indirectly, e.g., by affecting the enzyme acetylcholinesterase, which degrades the receptor ligand.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Agonists increase the level of receptor activation; antagonists reduce it.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Acetylcholine itself does not have therapeutic value as a drug for intravenous administration because of its multi-faceted action (non-selective) and rapid inactivation by cholinesterase.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] However, it is used in the form of eye drops to cause constriction of the pupil during cataract surgery, which facilitates quick post-operational recovery.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Nicotine binds to and activates nicotinic acetylcholine receptors, mimicking the effect of acetylcholine at these receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] ACh opens a **Na+** **channel** upon binding so that Na+ flows into the cell.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] This causes a depolarization, and results in an excitatory post-synaptic potential.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Thus, ACh is excitatory on skeletal muscle; the electrical response is fast and short-lived.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Curares are arrow poisons, which act at nicotinic receptors and have been used to develop clinically useful therapies.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Muscarinic receptors form **G protein-coupled receptor** complexes in the cell membranes of neurons and other cells.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Atropine is a non-selective competitive antagonist with Acetylcholine at muscarinic receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Many ACh receptor agonists work indirectly by inhibiting the enzyme acetylcholinesterase.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The resulting accumulation of acetylcholine causes continuous stimulation of the muscles, glands, and central nervous system, which can result in fatal convulsions if the dose is high.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] They are examples of enzyme inhibitors, and increase the action of acetylcholine by delaying its degradation; some have been used as nerve agents (Sarin and VX nerve gas) or pesticides (organophosphates and the carbamates).
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Many toxins and venoms produced by plants and animals also contain cholinesterase inhibitors.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] In clinical use, they are administered in low doses to reverse the action of muscle relaxants, to treat myasthenia gravis, and to treat symptoms of Alzheimer's disease (rivastigmine, which increases cholinergic activity in the brain).
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Organic mercurial compounds, such as methylmercury, have a high affinity for sulfhydryl groups, which causes dysfunction of the enzyme choline acetyltransferase.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] This inhibition may lead to acetylcholine deficiency, and can have consequences on motor function.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Botulinum toxin (Botox) acts by suppressing the release of acetylcholine, whereas the venom from a black widow spider (alpha-latrotoxin) has the reverse effect.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] When bitten by a black widow spider, one experiences the wastage of ACh supplies and the muscles begin to contract.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] If and when the supply is depleted, paralysis occurs.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Photopharmacology is an emerging field that uses light to control the activity of biologically active compounds with high spatial and temporal precision.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] These light-regulated compounds, based on either photolabile protecting groups ("caged" ligands) or photoisomerizable scaffolds, offer unprecedented control over acetylcholine-mediated processes and represent promising tools for both basic research and potential therapeutic applications.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Acetylcholine is used by organisms in all domains of life for a variety of purposes.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] It is believed that choline, a precursor to acetylcholine, was used by single celled organisms billions of years ago for synthesizing cell membrane phospholipids.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Following the evolution of choline transporters, the abundance of intracellular choline paved the way for choline to become incorporated into other synthetic pathways, including acetylcholine production.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Acetylcholine is used by bacteria, fungi, and a variety of other animals.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Many of the uses of acetylcholine rely on its action on ion channels via GPCRs like membrane proteins.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The two major types of acetylcholine receptors, muscarinic and nicotinic receptors, have convergently evolved to be responsive to acetylcholine.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] This means that rather than having evolved from a common homolog, these receptors evolved from separate receptor families.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] It is estimated that the nicotinic receptor family dates back longer than 2.5 billion years.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Likewise, muscarinic receptors are thought to have diverged from other GPCRs at least 0.5 billion years ago.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Both of these receptor groups have evolved numerous subtypes with unique ligand affinities and signaling mechanisms.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The diversity of the receptor types enables acetylcholine to create varying responses depending on which receptor types are activated, and allow for acetylcholine to dynamically regulate physiological processes.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] ACh receptors are related to 5-HT3 (serotonin), GABA, and Glycine receptors, both in sequence and structure, strongly suggesting that they have a common evolutionary origin.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] In 1867, Adolf von Baeyer resolved the structures of choline and acetylcholine and synthesized them both, referring to the latter as *acetylneurin* in the study.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Choline is a precursor for acetylcholine.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Acetylcholine was first noted to be biologically active in 1906, when Reid Hunt (1870–1948) and René de M.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Taveau found that it decreased blood pressure in exceptionally tiny doses.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] This was after Frederick Walker Mott and William Dobinson Halliburton noted in 1899 that choline injections decreased the blood pressure of animals.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Ewins was the first to extract acetylcholine from nature.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] He identified it as the blood pressure-decreasing contaminant from some *Claviceps purpurea* ergot extracts, by the request of Henry Hallett Dale.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Later in 1914, Dale outlined the effects of acetylcholine at various types of peripheral synapses and also noted that it lowered the blood pressure of cats via subcutaneous injections even at doses of one nanogram.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] The concept of neurotransmitters was unknown until 1921, when Otto Loewi noted that the vagus nerve secreted a substance that inhibited the heart muscle whilst working as a professor in the University of Graz.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] He named it *vagusstoff* ("vagus substance"), noted it to be a structural analog of choline and suspected it to be acetylcholine.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Navratil deduced that the compound is probably acetylcholine, as vagusstoff and synthetic acetylcholine lost their activity in a similar manner when in contact with tissue lysates that contained acetylcholine-degrading enzymes (now known to be cholinesterases).
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Later studies confirmed the function of acetylcholine as a neurotransmitter.
[src:neurotransmitters/acetylcholine] Loewi shared the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their studies of acetylcholine and nerve impulses.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Outside the central nervous system, dopamine functions primarily as a local paracrine messenger.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] With the exception of the blood vessels, dopamine in each of these peripheral systems is synthesized locally and exerts its effects near the cells that release it.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Several important diseases of the nervous system are associated with dysfunctions of the dopamine system, and some of the key medications used to treat them work by altering the effects of dopamine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Parkinson's disease, a degenerative condition causing tremor and motor impairment, is caused by a loss of dopamine-secreting neurons in an area of the midbrain called the substantia nigra.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Its metabolic precursor L-DOPA can be manufactured; *Levodopa*, a pure form of L-DOPA, is the most widely used treatment for Parkinson's.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] There is evidence that schizophrenia involves altered levels of dopamine activity, and most antipsychotic drugs used to treat this are dopamine antagonists which reduce dopamine activity.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Similar dopamine antagonist drugs are also some of the most effective anti-nausea agents.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Restless legs syndrome and attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) are associated with decreased dopamine activity.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopaminergic stimulants can be addictive in high doses, but some are used at lower doses to treat ADHD.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine itself is available as a manufactured medication for intravenous injection.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] It is useful in the treatment of severe heart failure or cardiogenic shock.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In newborn babies it may be used for hypotension and septic shock.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] A dopamine molecule consists of a catechol structure (a benzene ring with two hydroxyl side groups) with one amine group attached via an ethyl chain.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] As such, dopamine is the simplest possible catecholamine, a family that also includes the neurotransmitters norepinephrine and epinephrine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The presence of a benzene ring with this amine attachment makes it a substituted phenethylamine, a family that includes numerous psychoactive drugs.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Like most amines, dopamine is an organic base.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] As a base, it is generally protonated in acidic environments (in an acid-base reaction).
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The protonated form is highly water-soluble and relatively stable, but can become oxidized if exposed to oxygen or other oxidants.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In basic environments, dopamine is not protonated.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In this free base form, it is less water-soluble and also more highly reactive.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Because of the increased stability and water-solubility of the protonated form, dopamine is supplied for chemical or pharmaceutical use as dopamine hydrochloride—that is, the hydrochloride salt that is created when dopamine is combined with hydrochloric acid.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In dry form, dopamine hydrochloride is a fine powder which is white to yellow in color.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine is synthesized in a restricted set of cell types, mainly neurons and cells in the medulla of the adrenal glands.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The direct precursor of dopamine, L-DOPA, can be synthesized indirectly from the essential amino acid phenylalanine or directly from the non-essential amino acid tyrosine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] These amino acids are found in nearly every protein and so are readily available in food, with tyrosine being the most common.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Although dopamine is also found in many types of food, it is incapable of crossing the blood–brain barrier that surrounds and protects the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] It must therefore be synthesized inside the brain to perform its neuronal activity.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] L-Phenylalanine is converted into L-tyrosine by the enzyme phenylalanine hydroxylase, with molecular oxygen (O2) and tetrahydrobiopterin as cofactors.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] L-Tyrosine is converted into L-DOPA by the enzyme tyrosine hydroxylase, with tetrahydrobiopterin, O2, and iron (Fe2+) as cofactors.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] L-DOPA is converted into dopamine by the enzyme aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase (also known as DOPA decarboxylase), with pyridoxal phosphate as the cofactor.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine itself is used as precursor in the synthesis of the neurotransmitters norepinephrine and epinephrine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine is converted into norepinephrine by the enzyme dopamine β-hydroxylase, with O2 and L-ascorbic acid as cofactors.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Norepinephrine is converted into epinephrine by the enzyme phenylethanolamine *N*-methyltransferase with *S*-adenosyl-L-methionine as the cofactor.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Some of the cofactors also require their own synthesis.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Deficiency in any required amino acid or cofactor can impair the synthesis of dopamine, norepinephrine, and epinephrine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine is broken down into inactive metabolites by a set of enzymes—monoamine oxidase (MAO), catechol-*O*-methyl transferase (COMT), and aldehyde dehydrogenase (ALDH), acting in sequence.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Both isoforms of monoamine oxidase, MAO-A and MAO-B, effectively metabolize dopamine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Different breakdown pathways exist but the main end-product is homovanillic acid (HVA), which has no known biological activity.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] From the bloodstream, homovanillic acid is filtered out by the kidneys and then excreted in the urine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In clinical research on schizophrenia, measurements of homovanillic acid in plasma have been used to estimate levels of dopamine activity in the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] A difficulty in this approach, however, is separating the high level of plasma homovanillic acid contributed by the metabolism of norepinephrine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Although dopamine is normally broken down by an oxidoreductase enzyme, it is also susceptible to oxidation by direct reaction with oxygen, yielding quinones plus various free radicals as products.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The rate of oxidation can be increased by the presence of ferric iron or other factors.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Quinones and free radicals produced by autoxidation of dopamine can poison cells, and there is evidence that this mechanism may contribute to the cell loss that occurs in Parkinson's disease and other conditions.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine exerts its effects by binding to and activating cell surface receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In humans, dopamine has a high binding affinity at dopamine receptors and human trace amine-associated receptor 1 (hTAAR1).
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In mammals, five subtypes of dopamine receptors have been identified, labeled from D1 to D5.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] All of them function as metabotropic, G protein-coupled receptors, meaning that they exert their effects via a complex second messenger system.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] These receptors can be divided into two families, known as D1-like and D2-like.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Consequently, it is incorrect to describe dopamine itself as either excitatory or inhibitory: its effect on a target neuron depends on which types of receptors are present on the membrane of that neuron and on the internal responses of that neuron to the second messenger cAMP.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] D1 receptors are the most numerous dopamine receptors in the human nervous system; D2 receptors are next; D3, D4, and D5 receptors are present at significantly lower levels.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Inside the brain, dopamine functions as a neurotransmitter and neuromodulator, and is controlled by a set of mechanisms common to all monoamine neurotransmitters.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] After synthesis, dopamine is transported from the cytosol into secretory vesicles, including synaptic vesicles, small and large dense core vesicles by a solute carrier—a vesicular monoamine transporter, VMAT2.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine is stored in these vesicles until it is ejected into the synaptic cleft.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In most cases, the release of dopamine occurs through a process called exocytosis which is caused by action potentials, but it can also be caused by the activity of an intracellular trace amine-associated receptor, TAAR1.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Once in the synapse, dopamine binds to and activates dopamine receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] These can be postsynaptic dopamine receptors, which are located on dendrites (the postsynaptic neuron), or presynaptic autoreceptors (e.g., the D2sh and presynaptic D3 receptors), which are located on the membrane of an axon terminal (the presynaptic neuron).
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] After the postsynaptic neuron elicits an action potential, dopamine molecules quickly become unbound from their receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] They are then absorbed back into the presynaptic cell, via reuptake mediated either by the dopamine transporter or by the plasma membrane monoamine transporter.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Once back in the cytosol, dopamine can either be broken down by a monoamine oxidase or repackaged into vesicles by VMAT2, making it available for future release.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In the brain the level of extracellular dopamine is modulated by two mechanisms: phasic and tonic transmission.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Phasic dopamine release, like most neurotransmitter release in the nervous system, is driven directly by action potentials in the dopamine-containing cells.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Tonic dopamine transmission occurs when small amounts of dopamine are released without being preceded by presynaptic action potentials.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Tonic transmission is regulated by a variety of factors, including the activity of other neurons and neurotransmitter reuptake.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Protein dopaminylation refers to the post-translational modification in which dopamine is covalently attached to glutamine residues via transamidation.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In general, protein monoaminylation refers to the *overall class* of post-translational modifications involving monoamines; however, these reactions are further classified by the individual monoamine reactant they describe (i.e., dopaminylation, serotonylation, histaminylation).
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopaminylation has been reported for both histone and non-histone protein substrates, and thus represents a distinct neuroepigenetic and neuroproteomic regulatory mechanism with various implications in health and disease.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Recent studies have unveiled a critical role for dopaminylation in mediating a wide range of physiological processes, be that in the nervous system or beyond.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopaminylation is catalyzed by transglutaminase 2 (TGM2) in a calcium-dependent manner, and relies upon the intracellular bioavailability of dopamine substrates.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Generally, protein dopaminylation occurs in the cytoplasm; however, histone dopaminylation only occurs within the nucleus.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] To date, histone H3 is the only histone protein known to undergo monoaminylation modifications, which have only been reported for glutamine position 5 (Gln5) of histone H3.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] H3Q5-dopaminylation (H3Q5dop) in particular has remained a seldom explored topic since its discovery in 2020.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Histone serotonylation remains the most widely reported histone monoaminylation modification to date, though both histone dopaminylation and histone histaminylation have also been reported.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Nevertheless, H3Q5dop has been reported in dopaminergic neurons of the nucleus accumbens (NAc), ventral tegmental area (VTA), and amygdala.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] H3Q5-dopaminylation has been implicated in a variety of processes, including cocaine-induced transcriptional plasticity, heroin-induced transcriptional and behavioral plasticity, and drug-induced transcriptional and behavioral changes.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Inside the brain, dopamine plays important roles in executive functions, motor control, motivation, arousal, reinforcement, and reward, as well as lower-level functions including lactation, sexual gratification, and nausea.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The dopaminergic cell groups and pathways make up the dopamine system which is neuromodulatory.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopaminergic neurons (dopamine-producing nerve cells) are comparatively few in number—a total of around 400,000 in the human brain—and their cell bodies are confined in groups to a few relatively small brain areas.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] However their axons project to many other brain areas, and they exert powerful effects on their targets.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] These dopaminergic cell groups were first mapped in 1964 by Annica Dahlström and Kjell Fuxe, who assigned them labels starting with the letter "A" (for "aminergic").
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In their scheme, areas A1 through A7 contain the neurotransmitter norepinephrine, whereas A8 through A14 contain dopamine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The dopaminergic areas they identified are the substantia nigra (groups 8 and 9); the ventral tegmental area (group 10); the posterior hypothalamus (group 11); the arcuate nucleus (group 12); the zona incerta (group 13) and the periventricular nucleus (group 14).
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The substantia nigra is a small midbrain area that forms a component of the basal ganglia.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] This has two parts—an input area called the pars reticulata and an output area called the pars compacta.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The dopaminergic neurons are found mainly in the pars compacta (cell group A8) and nearby (group A9).
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In humans, the projection of dopaminergic neurons from the substantia nigra pars compacta to the dorsal striatum, termed the *nigrostriatal pathway*, plays a significant role in the control of motor function and in learning new motor skills.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] These neurons are especially vulnerable to damage, and when a large number of them die, the result is a parkinsonian syndrome.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The ventral tegmental area (VTA) is another midbrain area.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The most prominent group of VTA dopaminergic neurons projects to the prefrontal cortex via the mesocortical pathway and another smaller group projects to the nucleus accumbens via the mesolimbic pathway.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Together, these two pathways are collectively termed the *mesocorticolimbic projection*.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The VTA also sends dopaminergic projections to the amygdala, cingulate gyrus, hippocampus, and olfactory bulb.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Mesocorticolimbic neurons play a central role in reward and other aspects of motivation.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Accumulating literature shows that dopamine also plays a crucial role in aversive learning through its effects on a number of brain regions.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The posterior hypothalamus has dopamine neurons that project to the spinal cord, but their function is not well established.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] There is some evidence that pathology in this area plays a role in restless legs syndrome, a condition in which people have difficulty sleeping due to an overwhelming compulsion to constantly move parts of the body, especially the legs.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The arcuate nucleus and the periventricular nucleus of the hypothalamus have dopamine neurons that form an important projection—the *tuberoinfundibular pathway* which goes to the pituitary gland, where it influences the secretion of the hormone prolactin.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine is the primary neuroendocrine inhibitor of the secretion of prolactin from the anterior pituitary gland.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine produced by neurons in the arcuate nucleus is secreted into the hypophyseal portal system of the median eminence, which supplies the pituitary gland.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The prolactin cells that produce prolactin, in the absence of dopamine, secrete prolactin continuously; dopamine inhibits this secretion.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The zona incerta, grouped between the arcuate and periventricular nuclei, projects to several areas of the hypothalamus, and participates in the control of gonadotropin-releasing hormone, which is necessary to activate the development of the male and female reproductive systems, following puberty.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] An additional group of dopamine-secreting neurons is found in the retina of the eye.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] These neurons are amacrine cells, meaning that they have no axons.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] They release dopamine into the extracellular medium, and are specifically active during daylight hours, becoming silent at night.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] This retinal dopamine acts to enhance the activity of cone cells in the retina while suppressing rod cells—the result is to increase sensitivity to color and contrast during bright light conditions, at the cost of reduced sensitivity when the light is dim.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The largest and most important sources of dopamine in the vertebrate brain are the substantia nigra and ventral tegmental area.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Both structures are components of the midbrain, closely related to each other and functionally similar in many respects.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The largest component of the basal ganglia is the striatum.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The substantia nigra sends a dopaminergic projection to the dorsal striatum, while the ventral tegmental area sends a similar type of dopaminergic projection to the ventral striatum.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Progress in understanding the functions of the basal ganglia has been slow.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The most popular hypotheses, broadly stated, propose that the basal ganglia play a central role in action selection.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Thus the basal ganglia, in this concept, are responsible for initiating behaviors, but not for determining the details of how they are carried out.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In other words, they essentially form a decision-making system.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The basal ganglia can be divided into several sectors, and each is involved in controlling particular types of actions.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The ventral sector of the basal ganglia (containing the ventral striatum which receives projections from ventral tegmental area) operates at the highest level of the hierarchy, selecting actions at the whole-organism level.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The dorsal sectors (containing the dorsal striatum which receives projections from substantia nigra) operate at lower levels, selecting the specific muscles and movements that are used to implement a given behavior pattern.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine contributes to the action selection process in at least two important ways.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] First, it sets the "threshold" for initiating actions.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The higher the level of dopamine activity, the lower the impetus required to evoke a given behavior.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] As a consequence, high levels of dopamine lead to high levels of motor activity and impulsive behavior; low levels of dopamine lead to torpor and slowed reactions.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In the opposite direction, drugs that increase dopamine release, such as cocaine or amphetamine, can produce heightened levels of activity, including, at the extreme, psychomotor agitation and stereotyped movements.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The second important effect of dopamine is as a "teaching" signal.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] When an action is followed by an increase in dopamine activity, the basal ganglia circuit is altered in a way that makes the same response easier to evoke when similar situations arise in the future.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] This is a form of operant conditioning, in which dopamine plays the role of a reward signal.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In the language used to discuss the reward system, *reward* is the attractive and motivational property of a stimulus that induces appetitive behavior (also known as approach behavior) and consummatory behavior.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] A rewarding stimulus is one that can induce the organism to approach it and choose to consume it.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Pleasure, learning (e.g., classical and operant conditioning), and approach behavior are the three main functions of reward.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] As an aspect of reward, *pleasure* provides a definition of reward; however, while all pleasurable stimuli are rewarding, not all rewarding stimuli are pleasurable (e.g., extrinsic rewards like money).
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The motivational or desirable aspect of rewarding stimuli is reflected by the approach behavior that they induce, whereas the pleasure from intrinsic rewards results from consuming them after acquiring them.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In human drug addicts, "wanting" becomes dissociated with "liking" as the desire to use an addictive drug increases, while the pleasure obtained from consuming it decreases due to drug tolerance.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Within the brain, dopamine functions partly as a global reward signal.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] An initial dopamine response to a rewarding stimulus encodes information about the salience, value, and context of a reward.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In the context of reward-related learning, dopamine also functions as a *reward prediction error* signal, that is, the degree to which the value of a reward is unexpected.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The "prediction error" hypothesis has drawn particular interest from computational neuroscientists, because an influential computational-learning method known as temporal difference learning makes heavy use of a signal that encodes prediction error.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] This confluence of theory and data has led to a fertile interaction between neuroscientists and computer scientists interested in machine learning.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Evidence from microelectrode recordings from the brains of animals shows that dopamine neurons in the ventral tegmental area (VTA) and substantia nigra are strongly activated by a wide variety of rewarding events.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] These reward-responsive dopamine neurons in the VTA and substantia nigra are crucial for reward-related cognition and serve as the central component of the reward system.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Some activity within the VTA dopaminergic projections appears to be associated with reward prediction as well.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] While dopamine has a central role in causing "wanting," associated with the appetitive or approach behavioral responses to rewarding stimuli, detailed studies have shown that dopamine cannot simply be equated with hedonic "liking" or pleasure, as reflected in the consummatory behavioral response.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine neurotransmission is involved in some but not all aspects of pleasure-related cognition, since pleasure centers have been identified both within the dopamine system (i.e., nucleus accumbens shell) and outside the dopamine system (i.e., ventral pallidum and parabrachial nucleus).
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] For example, direct electrical stimulation of dopamine pathways, using electrodes implanted in the brain, is experienced as pleasurable, and many types of animals are willing to work to obtain it.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Antipsychotic drugs reduce dopamine levels and tend to cause anhedonia, a diminished ability to experience pleasure.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Many types of pleasurable experiences—such as sexual intercourse, eating, and playing video games—increase dopamine release.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] All addictive drugs directly or indirectly affect dopamine neurotransmission in the nucleus accumbens; these drugs increase drug "wanting", leading to compulsive drug use, when repeatedly taken in high doses, presumably through the sensitization of incentive-salience.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Drugs that increase synaptic dopamine concentrations include psychostimulants such as methamphetamine and cocaine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] These produce increases in "wanting" behaviors, but do not greatly alter expressions of pleasure or change levels of satiation.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] However, opiate drugs such as heroin and morphine produce increases in expressions of "liking" and "wanting" behaviors.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Moreover, animals in which the ventral tegmental dopamine system has been rendered inactive do not seek food, and will starve to death if left to themselves, but if food is placed in their mouths they will consume it and show expressions indicative of pleasure.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] This research demonstrated that increased dopamine neurotransmission acts as a *sine qua non* condition for pleasurable hedonic reactions to music in humans.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] A study published in Nature in 1998 found evidence that playing video games releases dopamine in the human striatum.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] This dopamine is associated with learning, behavior reinforcement, attention, and sensorimotor integration.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Researchers used positron emission tomography scans and 11C-labelled raclopride to track dopamine levels in the brain during goal-directed motor tasks and found that dopamine release was positively correlated with task performance and was greatest in the ventral striatum.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] This was the first study to demonstrate the behavioral conditions under which dopamine is released in humans.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] It highlights the ability of positron emission tomography to detect neurotransmitter fluxes during changes in behavior.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] According to research, potentially problematic video game use is related to personality traits such as low self-esteem and low self-efficacy, anxiety, aggression, and clinical symptoms of depression and anxiety disorders.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Additionally, the reasons individuals play video games vary and may include coping, socialization, and personal satisfaction.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The DSM-5 defines Internet Gaming Disorder as a mental disorder closely related to Gambling Disorder.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] This has been supported by some researchers but has also caused controversy.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine does not cross the blood–brain barrier, so its synthesis and functions in peripheral areas are to a large degree independent of its synthesis and functions in the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] A substantial amount of dopamine circulates in the bloodstream, but its functions there are not entirely clear.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine is found in blood plasma at levels comparable to those of epinephrine, but in humans, over 95% of the dopamine in the plasma is in the form of dopamine sulfate, a conjugate produced by the enzyme sulfotransferase 1A3/1A4 acting on free dopamine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The bulk of this dopamine sulfate is produced in the mesenteric organs.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The production of dopamine sulfate is thought to be a mechanism for detoxifying dopamine that is ingested as food or produced by the digestive process—levels in the plasma typically rise more than fifty-fold after a meal.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine sulfate has no known biological functions and is excreted in urine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The relatively small quantity of unconjugated dopamine in the bloodstream may be produced by the sympathetic nervous system, the digestive system, or possibly other organs.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] It may act on dopamine receptors in peripheral tissues, or be metabolized, or be converted to norepinephrine by the enzyme dopamine beta hydroxylase, which is released into the bloodstream by the adrenal medulla.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] These responses might be activated by dopamine released from the carotid body under conditions of low oxygen, but whether arterial dopamine receptors perform other biologically useful functions is not known.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Beyond its role in modulating blood flow, there are several peripheral systems in which dopamine circulates within a limited area and performs an exocrine or paracrine function.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The peripheral systems in which dopamine plays an important role include the immune system, the kidneys and the pancreas.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In the immune system dopamine acts upon receptors present on immune cells, especially lymphocytes.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine can also affect immune cells in the spleen, bone marrow, and circulatory system.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In addition, dopamine can be synthesized and released by immune cells themselves.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The main effect of dopamine on lymphocytes is to reduce their activation level.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The functional significance of this system is unclear, but it affords a possible route for interactions between the nervous system and immune system, and may be relevant to some autoimmune disorders.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The renal dopaminergic system is located in the cells of the nephron in the kidney, where all subtypes of dopamine receptors are present.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine is also synthesized there, by tubule cells, and discharged into the tubular fluid.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Its actions include increasing the blood supply to the kidneys, increasing the glomerular filtration rate, and increasing the excretion of sodium in the urine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Hence, defects in renal dopamine function can lead to reduced sodium excretion and consequently result in the development of high blood pressure.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] There is strong evidence that faults in the production of dopamine or in the receptors can result in a number of pathologies including oxidative stress, edema, and either genetic or essential hypertension.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Oxidative stress can itself cause hypertension.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Defects in the system can also be caused by genetic factors or high blood pressure.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] In the pancreas the role of dopamine is somewhat complex.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The pancreas consists of two parts, an exocrine and an endocrine component.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The exocrine part synthesizes and secretes digestive enzymes and other substances, including dopamine, into the small intestine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The function of this secreted dopamine after it enters the small intestine is not clearly established—the possibilities include protecting the intestinal mucosa from damage and reducing gastrointestinal motility (the rate at which content moves through the digestive system).
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The pancreatic islets make up the endocrine part of the pancreas, and synthesize and secrete hormones including insulin into the bloodstream.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] There is evidence that the beta cells in the islets that synthesize insulin contain dopamine receptors, and that dopamine acts to reduce the amount of insulin they release.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The source of their dopamine input is not clearly established—it may come from dopamine that circulates in the bloodstream and derives from the sympathetic nervous system, or it may be synthesized locally by other types of pancreatic cells.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Dopamine as a manufactured medication is sold under the trade names Intropin, Dopastat, and Revimine, among others.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] It is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] It is most commonly used as a stimulant drug in the treatment of severe low blood pressure, slow heart rate, and cardiac arrest.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] It is especially important in treating these in newborn infants.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Since the half-life of dopamine in plasma is very short—approximately one minute in adults, two minutes in newborn infants and up to five minutes in preterm infants—it is usually given in a continuous intravenous drip rather than a single injection.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Its effects, depending on dosage, include an increase in sodium excretion by the kidneys, an increase in urine output, an increase in heart rate, and an increase in blood pressure.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] At low doses it acts through the sympathetic nervous system to increase heart muscle contraction force and heart rate, thereby increasing cardiac output and blood pressure.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Higher doses also cause vasoconstriction that further increases blood pressure.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Older literature also describes very low doses thought to improve kidney function without other consequences, but recent reviews have concluded that doses at such low levels are not effective and may sometimes be harmful.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] While some effects result from stimulation of dopamine receptors, the prominent cardiovascular effects result from dopamine acting at α1, β1, and β2 adrenergic receptors as a weak agonist.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] Side effects of dopamine include negative effects on kidney function and irregular heartbeats.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p01] The LD50, or lethal dose which is expected to prove fatal in 50% of the population, has been found to be: 59 mg/kg (mouse; administered intravenously); 95 mg/kg (mouse; administered intraperitoneally); 163 mg/kg (rat; administered intraperitoneally); 79 mg/kg (dog; administered intravenously).
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The dopamine system plays a central role in several significant medical conditions, including Parkinson's disease, attention deficit hyperactivity disorder, Tourette syndrome, schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, and addiction.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Aside from dopamine itself, there are many other important drugs that act on dopamine systems in various parts of the brain or body.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] A number of studies have reported an age-related decline in dopamine synthesis and dopamine receptor density (i.e., the number of receptors) in the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] This decline has been shown to occur in the striatum and extrastriatal regions.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Decreases in the D1, D2, and D3 receptors are well documented.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The reduction of dopamine with aging is thought to be responsible for many neurological symptoms that increase in frequency with age, such as decreased arm swing and increased rigidity.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Changes in dopamine levels may also cause age-related changes in cognitive flexibility.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Studies reported that dopamine imbalance influences the fatigue in multiple sclerosis.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] In patients with multiple sclerosis, dopamine inhibits production of IL-17 and IFN-γ by peripheral blood mononuclear cells.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Parkinson's disease is an age-related disorder characterized by movement disorders such as stiffness of the body, slowing of movement, and trembling of limbs when they are not in use.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] In advanced stages it progresses to dementia and eventually death.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The main symptoms are caused by the loss of dopamine-secreting cells in the substantia nigra.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Most cases of Parkinson's disease, however, are idiopathic, meaning that the cause of cell death cannot be identified.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The most widely used treatment for parkinsonism is administration of L-DOPA, the metabolic precursor for dopamine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] L-DOPA is converted to dopamine in the brain and various parts of the body by the enzyme DOPA decarboxylase.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] L-DOPA is used rather than dopamine itself because, unlike dopamine, it is capable of crossing the blood–brain barrier.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] It is often co-administered with an enzyme inhibitor of peripheral decarboxylation such as carbidopa or benserazide, to reduce the amount converted to dopamine in the periphery and thereby increase the amount of L-DOPA that enters the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] When L-DOPA is administered regularly over a long time period, a variety of unpleasant side effects such as dyskinesia often begin to appear; even so, it is considered the best available long-term treatment option for most cases of Parkinson's disease.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] L-DOPA treatment cannot restore the dopamine cells that have been lost, but it causes the remaining cells to produce more dopamine, thereby compensating for the loss to at least some degree.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] In advanced stages the treatment begins to fail because the cell loss is so severe that the remaining ones cannot produce enough dopamine regardless of L-DOPA levels.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Other drugs that enhance dopamine function, such as bromocriptine and pergolide, are also sometimes used to treat Parkinsonism, but in most cases L-DOPA appears to give the best trade-off between positive effects and negative side-effects.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The latter behaviors are similar to those observed in individuals with a behavioral addiction.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Cocaine, substituted amphetamines (including methamphetamine), Adderall, methylphenidate (marketed as Ritalin or Concerta), and other psychostimulants exert their effects primarily or partly by increasing dopamine levels in the brain by a variety of mechanisms.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Cocaine and methylphenidate are dopamine transporter blockers or reuptake inhibitors; they non-competitively inhibit dopamine reuptake, resulting in increased dopamine concentrations in the synaptic cleft.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Like cocaine, substituted amphetamines and amphetamine also increase the concentration of dopamine in the synaptic cleft, but by different mechanisms.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The effects of psychostimulants include increases in heart rate, body temperature, and sweating; improvements in alertness, attention, and endurance; increases in pleasure produced by rewarding events; but at higher doses agitation, anxiety, or even loss of contact with reality.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Drugs in this group can have a high addiction potential, due to their activating effects on the dopamine-mediated reward system in the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] However some can also be useful, at lower doses, for treating attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) and narcolepsy.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] An important differentiating factor is the onset and duration of action.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Cocaine can take effect in seconds if it is injected or inhaled in free base form; the effects last from 5 to 90 minutes.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] This rapid and brief action makes its effects easily perceived and consequently gives it high addiction potential.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Methylphenidate taken in pill form, in contrast, can take two hours to reach peak levels in the bloodstream, and depending on formulation the effects can last for up to 12 hours.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] These longer acting formulations have the benefit of reducing the potential for abuse, and improving adherence for treatment by using more convenient dosage regimens.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] A variety of addictive drugs produce an increase in reward-related dopamine activity.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Stimulants such as nicotine, cocaine and methamphetamine promote increased levels of dopamine which appear to be the primary factor in causing addiction.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] For other addictive drugs such as the opioid heroin, the increased levels of dopamine in the reward system may play only a minor role in addiction.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The dopamine system plays a crucial role in several aspects of addiction.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] At the earliest stage, genetic differences that alter the expression of dopamine receptors in the brain can predict whether a person will find stimulants appealing or aversive.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Consumption of stimulants produces increases in brain dopamine levels that last from minutes to hours.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Finally, the chronic elevation in dopamine that comes with repetitive high-dose stimulant consumption triggers a wide-ranging set of structural changes in the brain that are responsible for the behavioral abnormalities which characterize an addiction.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Treatment of stimulant addiction is very difficult, because even if consumption ceases, the craving that comes with psychological withdrawal does not.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Even when the craving seems to be extinct, it may re-emerge when faced with stimuli that are associated with the drug, such as friends, locations and situations.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Association networks in the brain are greatly interlinked.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Psychiatrists in the early 1950s discovered that a class of drugs known as typical antipsychotics (also known as major tranquilizers), were often effective at reducing the psychotic symptoms of schizophrenia.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The introduction of the first widely used antipsychotic, chlorpromazine (Thorazine), in the 1950s, led to the release of many patients with schizophrenia from institutions in the years that followed.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] By the 1970s researchers understood that these typical antipsychotics worked as antagonists on the D2 receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] This realization led to the so-called dopamine hypothesis of schizophrenia, which postulates that schizophrenia is largely caused by hyperactivity of brain dopamine systems.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The dopamine hypothesis drew additional support from the observation that psychotic symptoms were often intensified by dopamine-enhancing stimulants such as methamphetamine, and that these drugs could also produce psychosis in healthy people if taken in large enough doses.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] In the following decades other atypical antipsychotics that had fewer serious side effects were developed.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Many of these newer drugs do not act directly on dopamine receptors, but instead produce alterations in dopamine activity indirectly.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] These drugs were also used to treat other psychoses.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Antipsychotic drugs have a broadly suppressive effect on most types of active behavior, and particularly reduce the delusional and agitated behavior characteristic of overt psychosis.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Later observations, however, have caused the dopamine hypothesis to lose popularity, at least in its simple original form.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] For one thing, patients with schizophrenia do not typically show measurably increased levels of brain dopamine activity.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Even so, many psychiatrists and neuroscientists continue to believe that schizophrenia involves some sort of dopamine system dysfunction.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] As the "dopamine hypothesis" has evolved over time, however, the sorts of dysfunctions it postulates have tended to become increasingly subtle and complex.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Stahl suggested in a review of 2018 that in many cases of psychosis, including schizophrenia, three interconnected networks based on dopamine, serotonin, and glutamate – each on its own or in various combinations – contributed to an overexcitation of dopamine D2 receptors in the ventral striatum.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] There are genetic links between dopamine receptors, the dopamine transporter, and ADHD, in addition to links to other neurotransmitter receptors and transporters.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The most important relationship between dopamine and ADHD involves the drugs that are used to treat ADHD.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Some of the most effective therapeutic agents for ADHD are psychostimulants such as methylphenidate (Ritalin, Concerta) and amphetamine (Evekeo, Adderall, Dexedrine), drugs that increase both dopamine and norepinephrine levels in the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The clinical effects of these psychostimulants in treating ADHD are mediated through the indirect activation of dopamine and norepinephrine receptors, specifically dopamine receptor D1 and adrenoceptor α2, in the prefrontal cortex.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Dopamine plays a role in pain processing in multiple levels of the central nervous system including the spinal cord, periaqueductal gray, thalamus, basal ganglia, and cingulate cortex.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Decreased levels of dopamine have been associated with painful symptoms that frequently occur in Parkinson's disease.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Abnormalities in dopaminergic neurotransmission also occur in several painful clinical conditions, including burning mouth syndrome, fibromyalgia, and restless legs syndrome.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Nausea and vomiting are largely determined by activity in the area postrema in the medulla of the brainstem, in a region known as the chemoreceptor trigger zone.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] This area contains a large population of type D2 dopamine receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Consequently, drugs that activate D2 receptors have a high potential to cause nausea.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] This group includes some medications that are administered for Parkinson's disease, as well as other dopamine agonists such as apomorphine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] In some cases, D2-receptor antagonists such as metoclopramide are useful as anti-nausea drugs.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Simultaneous positron emission tomography (PET) and functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI), have shown that the amount of dopamine release is dependent on the strength of conditioned fear response and is linearly coupled to learning-induced activity in the amygdala.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Dopamine is generally linked to reward learning, but it also plays a key role in fear learning and extinction by helping to form, store and update fear memories through its interaction with other brain regions like amygdala, ventromedial prefrontal cortex and striatum.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] There are no reports of dopamine in archaea, but it has been detected in some types of bacteria and in the protozoan called *Tetrahymena*.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Perhaps more importantly, there are types of bacteria that contain homologs of all the enzymes that animals use to synthesize dopamine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Dopamine is used as a neurotransmitter in most multicellular animals.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] In sponges there is only a single report of the presence of dopamine, with no indication of its function; however, dopamine has been reported in the nervous systems of many other radially symmetric species, including the cnidarian jellyfish, hydra and some corals.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] This dates the emergence of dopamine as a neurotransmitter back to the earliest appearance of the nervous system, over 500 million years ago in the Cambrian Period.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Dopamine functions as a neurotransmitter in vertebrates, echinoderms, arthropods, molluscs, and several types of worm.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] In every type of animal that has been examined, dopamine has been seen to modify motor behavior.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] In the model organism, nematode *Caenorhabditis elegans*, it reduces locomotion and increases food-exploratory movements; in flatworms it produces "screw-like" movements; in leeches it inhibits swimming and promotes crawling.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Across a wide range of vertebrates, dopamine has an "activating" effect on behavior-switching and response selection, comparable to its effect in mammals.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Dopamine has also consistently been shown to play a role in reward learning, in all animal groups.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] As in all vertebrates – invertebrates such as roundworms, flatworms, molluscs and common fruit flies can all be trained to repeat an action if it is consistently followed by an increase in dopamine levels.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] In fruit flies, distinct elements for reward learning suggest a modular structure to the insect reward processing system that broadly parallels that in the mammalian one.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] For example, dopamine regulates short- and long-term learning in monkeys; in fruit flies, different groups of dopamine neurons mediate reward signals for short- and long-term memories.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] It had long been believed that arthropods were an exception to this with dopamine being seen as having an adverse effect.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Reward was seen to be mediated instead by octopamine, a neurotransmitter closely related to norepinephrine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] More recent studies, however, have shown that dopamine does play a part in reward learning in fruit flies.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] It has also been found that the rewarding effect of octopamine is due to its activating a set of dopaminergic neurons not previously accessed in the research.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Dopamine can also be found in cephalopod ink.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Many plants, including a variety of food plants, synthesize dopamine to varying degrees.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The highest concentrations have been observed in bananas—the fruit pulp of red and yellow bananas contains dopamine at levels of 40 to 50 parts per million by weight.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Potatoes, avocados, broccoli, and Brussels sprouts may also contain dopamine at levels of 1 part per million or more; oranges, tomatoes, spinach, beans, and other plants contain measurable concentrations less than 1 part per million.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The dopamine in plants is synthesized from the amino acid tyrosine, by biochemical mechanisms similar to those that animals use.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] It can be metabolized in a variety of ways, producing melanin and a variety of alkaloids as byproducts.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The functions of plant catecholamines have not been clearly established, but there is evidence that they play a role in the response to stressors such as bacterial infection, act as growth-promoting factors in some situations, and modify the way that sugars are metabolized.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The receptors that mediate these actions have not yet been identified, nor have the intracellular mechanisms that they activate.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Dopamine consumed in food cannot act on the brain, because it cannot cross the blood–brain barrier.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] However, there are also a variety of plants that contain L-DOPA, the metabolic precursor of dopamine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The highest concentrations are found in the leaves and bean pods of plants of the genus *Mucuna*, especially in *Mucuna pruriens* (velvet beans), which have been used as a source for L-DOPA as a drug.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Another plant containing substantial amounts of L-DOPA is *Vicia faba*, the plant that produces fava beans (also known as "broad beans").
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The level of L-DOPA in the beans, however, is much lower than in the pod shells and other parts of the plant.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The seeds of *Cassia* and *Bauhinia* trees also contain substantial amounts of L-DOPA.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] In a species of marine green algae *Ulvaria obscura*, a major component of some algal blooms, dopamine is present in very high concentrations, estimated at 4.4% of dry weight.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] There is evidence that this dopamine functions as an anti-herbivore defense, reducing consumption by snails and isopods.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Melanins are a family of dark-pigmented substances found in a wide range of organisms.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Chemically they are closely related to dopamine, and there is a type of melanin, known as **dopamine-melanin**, that can be synthesized by oxidation of dopamine via the enzyme tyrosinase.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The melanin that darkens human skin is not of this type: it is synthesized by a pathway that uses L-DOPA as a precursor but not dopamine.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] However, there is substantial evidence that the neuromelanin that gives a dark color to the brain's substantia nigra is at least in part dopamine-melanin.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Dopamine-derived melanin probably appears in at least some other biological systems as well.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Some of the dopamine in plants is likely to be used as a precursor for dopamine-melanin.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The complex patterns that appear on butterfly wings, as well as black-and-white stripes on the bodies of insect larvae, are also thought to be caused by spatially structured accumulations of dopamine-melanin.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Dopamine was first synthesized in 1910 by George Barger and James Ewens at Wellcome Laboratories in London, England and first identified in the human brain by Katharine Montagu in 1957.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] It was named dopamine because it is a monoamine whose precursor in the Barger-Ewens synthesis is 3,4-**d**ihydr**o**xy**p**henyl**a**lanine (levodopa or L-DOPA).
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Dopamine's function as a neurotransmitter was first recognized in 1958 by Arvid Carlsson and Nils-Åke Hillarp at the Laboratory for Chemical Pharmacology of the National Heart Institute of Sweden.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Carlsson was awarded the 2000 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for showing that dopamine is not only a precursor of norepinephrine (noradrenaline) and epinephrine (adrenaline), but is also itself a neurotransmitter.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Research motivated by adhesive polyphenolic proteins in mussels led to the discovery in 2007 that a wide variety of materials, if placed in a solution of dopamine at slightly basic pH, will become coated with a layer of polymerized dopamine, often referred to as **polydopamine**.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] This polymerized dopamine forms by a spontaneous oxidation reaction, and is formally a type of melanin.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Furthermore, dopamine self-polymerization can be used to modulate the mechanical properties of peptide-based gels.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Synthesis of polydopamine usually involves reaction of dopamine hydrochloride with Tris as a base in water.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] The structure of polydopamine is unknown.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Polydopamine coatings can form on objects ranging in size from nanoparticles to large surfaces.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] Polydopamine layers have chemical properties that have the potential to be extremely useful, and numerous studies have examined their possible applications.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] At the simplest level, they can be used for protection against damage by light, or to form capsules for drug delivery.
[src:neurotransmitters/dopamine-p02] At a more sophisticated level, their adhesive properties may make them useful as substrates for biosensors or other biologically active macromolecules.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABA is sold as a dietary supplement in many countries.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] It has been traditionally thought that exogenous GABA (i.e., taken as a supplement) does not cross the blood–brain barrier, but data obtained from more recent research (2010s) in rats describes the notion as being unclear.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] The carboxylate form of GABA is **γ-aminobutyrate**.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Neurons that produce GABA as their output are called GABAergic neurons.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] In adult vertebrates, GABA is usually considered as the major inhibitory neurotransmitter.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] It also exhibits excitatory effect via GABAB receptor, in which case, a specific type of voltage dependent calcium channel is activated.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Medium spiny cells are a typical example of inhibitory central nervous system GABAergic cells.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] In contrast, GABA exhibits both excitatory and inhibitory actions in insects, mediating muscle activation at synapses between nerves and muscle cells, and also the stimulation of certain glands.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] In mammals, some GABAergic neurons, such as chandelier cells, are also able to excite their glutamatergic counterparts.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] In addition to fast-acting phasic inhibition, small amounts of extracellular GABA can induce slow timescale tonic inhibition on neurons.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABAA receptors are ligand-activated chloride channels: when activated by GABA, they allow the flow of chloride ions across the membrane of the cell.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Whether this chloride flow is depolarizing (makes the voltage across the cell's membrane less negative), shunting (has no effect on the cell's membrane potential), or inhibitory/hyperpolarizing (makes the cell's membrane more negative) depends on the direction of the flow of chloride.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] When net chloride flows out of the cell, GABA is depolarising; when chloride flows into the cell, GABA is inhibitory or hyperpolarizing.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] When the net flow of chloride is close to zero, the action of GABA is shunting.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Shunting inhibition has no direct effect on the membrane potential of the cell; however, it reduces the effect of any coincident synaptic input by reducing the electrical resistance of the cell's membrane.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Shunting inhibition can "override" the excitatory effect of depolarising GABA, resulting in overall inhibition even if the membrane potential becomes less negative.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] It was thought that a developmental switch in the molecular machinery controlling the concentration of chloride inside the cell changes the functional role of GABA between neonatal and adult stages.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] As the brain develops into adulthood, GABA's role changes from excitatory to inhibitory.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABA is an inhibitory transmitter in the mature brain; its actions were thought to be primarily excitatory in the developing brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] The gradient of chloride was reported to be reversed in immature neurons, with its reversal potential higher than the resting membrane potential of the cell; activation of a GABA-A receptor thus leads to efflux of Cl− ions from the cell (that is, a depolarizing current).
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] The differential gradient of chloride in immature neurons was shown to be primarily due to the higher concentration of NKCC1 co-transporters relative to KCC2 co-transporters in immature cells.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABAergic interneurons mature faster in the hippocampus and the GABA machinery appears earlier than glutamatergic transmission.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Thus, GABA is considered the major excitatory neurotransmitter in many regions of the brain before the maturation of glutamatergic synapses.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] In the developmental stages preceding the formation of synaptic contacts, GABA is synthesized by neurons and acts both as an autocrine (acting on the same cell) and paracrine (acting on nearby cells) signalling mediator.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] The ganglionic eminences also contribute greatly to building up the GABAergic cortical cell population.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABA regulates the proliferation of neural progenitor cells, the migration and differentiation the elongation of neurites and the formation of synapses.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABA also regulates the growth of embryonic and neural stem cells.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABA can influence the development of neural progenitor cells via brain-derived neurotrophic factor (BDNF) expression.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABA activates the GABAA receptor, causing cell cycle arrest in the S-phase, limiting growth.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Besides the nervous system, GABA is also produced at relatively high levels in the insulin-producing beta cells (β-cells) of the pancreas.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] The β-cells secrete GABA along with insulin and the GABA binds to GABA receptors on the neighboring islet alpha cells (α-cells) and inhibits them from secreting glucagon (which would counteract insulin's effects).
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABA can promote the replication and survival of β-cells and also promote the conversion of α-cells to β-cells, which may lead to new treatments for diabetes.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Alongside GABAergic mechanisms, GABA has also been detected in other peripheral tissues including intestines, stomach, fallopian tubes, uterus, ovaries, testicles, kidneys, urinary bladder, the lungs and liver, albeit at much lower levels than in neurons or β-cells.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Experiments on mice have shown that hypothyroidism induced by fluoride poisoning can be halted by administering GABA.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] The test also found that the thyroid recovered naturally without further assistance after the fluoride had been expelled by the GABA.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Immune cells express receptors for GABA and administration of GABA can suppress inflammatory immune responses and promote "regulatory" immune responses, such that GABA administration has been shown to inhibit autoimmune diseases in several animal models.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] In 2018, GABA was shown to regulate secretion of a greater number of cytokines.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] In plasma of T1D patients, levels of 26 cytokines are increased and of those, 16 are inhibited by GABA in the cell assays.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] In 2007, an excitatory GABAergic system was described in the airway epithelium.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] The system is activated by exposure to allergens and may participate in the mechanisms of asthma.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABAergic systems have also been found in the testis and in the eye lens.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABA is found mostly as a zwitterion (i.e., with the carboxyl group deprotonated and the amino group protonated).
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Its conformation depends on its environment.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] In the gas phase, a highly folded conformation is strongly favored due to the electrostatic attraction between the two functional groups.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] The stabilization is about 50 kcal/mol, according to quantum chemistry calculations.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] In the solid state, an extended conformation is found, with a trans conformation at the amino end and a gauche conformation at the carboxyl end.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] This is due to the packing interactions with the neighboring molecules.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] In solution, five different conformations, some folded and some extended, are found as a result of solvation effects.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] The conformational flexibility of GABA is important for its biological function, as it has been found to bind to different receptors with different conformations.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Many GABA analogues with pharmaceutical applications have more rigid structures in order to control the binding better.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABA was first synthesized in 1883; it was first known only as a plant and microbe metabolic product.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] In 1950, Washington University School of Medicine researchers Eugene Roberts and Sam Frankel used newly developed techniques of chromatography to analyze protein-free extracts of mammalian brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] They discovered that GABA is metabolized from glutamic acid and accumulates in the mammalian central nervous system.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] There was not much further research into the substance until 1957; Canadian researchers identified GABA as the mysterious component (termed Factor I by its discoverers in 1954) of brain and spinal cord extracts which inhibited crayfish neurons.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] In 1959, it was shown that, at an inhibitory synapse on crayfish muscle fibers, GABA acts through stimulation of the inhibitory nerve.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Both inhibition by nerve stimulation and by applied GABA are blocked by picrotoxin.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABA is primarily synthesized from glutamate via the enzyme glutamate decarboxylase (GAD) with pyridoxal phosphate (the active form of vitamin B6) as a cofactor.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] This process converts glutamate (the principal excitatory neurotransmitter) into GABA (the principal inhibitory neurotransmitter).
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABA can also be synthesized from putrescine by diamine oxidase and aldehyde dehydrogenase.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Historically it was thought that exogenous GABA did not penetrate the blood–brain barrier, but more current research describes the notion as being unclear pending further research.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABA transaminase enzymes catalyze the conversion of 4-aminobutanoic acid (GABA) and 2-oxoglutarate (α-ketoglutarate) into succinic semialdehyde and glutamate.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Succinic semialdehyde is then oxidized into succinic acid by succinic semialdehyde dehydrogenase and as such enters the citric acid cycle as a usable source of energy.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Drugs that act as allosteric modulators of GABA receptors (known as GABA analogues or *GABAergic* drugs), or increase the available amount of GABA, typically have relaxing, anti-anxiety, and anti-convulsive effects (with equivalent efficacy to lamotrigine based on studies of mice).
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Many of the substances below are known to cause anterograde amnesia and retrograde amnesia.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Lots of general anesthetics work by changing how GABA acts in the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Drugs such as propofol, etomidate, barbiturates, and many gases like isoflurane and sevoflurane cause GABAa receptors to become more active.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] When these receptors become more active, GABA open chloride channels for a longer time, which causes nerve cells to be less likely to send signals.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABAa receptors can become desensitized to GABA and stop opening when the ligand is attached.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Anesthetics work in two main ways: enhancing the effectiveness of GABA molecules, and manipulating the GABAa receptor to become less susceptible to desensitization.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] The slowing of brain activity from increased chloride movement causes the body to calm down, become drowsy, and eventually end up in an unconscious state that is needed for surgery.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Some anesthetics can even activate GABAa receptors without GABA even being present.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] The various types of GABA receptors have drug specific reactions which cause the differing effects of anesthetics.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] In general, GABA does not cross the blood–brain barrier, although certain areas of the brain that have no effective blood–brain barrier, such as the periventricular nucleus, can be reached by drugs such as systemically injected GABA.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] At least one study suggests that orally administered GABA increases the amount of human growth hormone (HGH).
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABA directly injected to the brain has been reported to have both stimulatory and inhibitory effects on the production of growth hormone, depending on the physiology of the individual.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Consequently, considering the potential biphasic effects of GABA on growth hormone production, as well as other safety concerns, its usage is not recommended during pregnancy and lactation.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABA enhances the catabolism of serotonin into *N*-acetylserotonin (the precursor of melatonin) in rat pineal glands (removed from the body, *ex vivo*).
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] It also depolarizes the GnRH-producing neurons *ex vivo* via their GABAA receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Melatonin modulates the strength of deploarization caused by the GABAA receptors *ex vivo* (rat brain tissue).
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] It is thus suspected that GABA is involved in the synthesis of melatonin and thus might exert regulatory effects on sleep and reproductive functions.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Although in chemical terms, GABA is an amino acid (as it has both a primary amine and a carboxylic acid functional group), it is rarely referred to as such in the professional, scientific, or medical community.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] By convention the term "amino acid", when used without a qualifier, refers specifically to an alpha amino acid.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABA is not an alpha amino acid, meaning the amino group is not attached to the alpha carbon.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Nor is it incorporated into proteins as are many alpha-amino acids.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABAA receptor ligands are shown in the following table.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] GABAergic pro-drugs include chloral hydrate, which is metabolised to trichloroethanol, which then acts via the GABAA receptor.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] The plant kava contains GABAergic compounds, including kavain, dihydrokavain, methysticin, dihydromethysticin and yangonin.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] 4-Amino-1-butanol is a biochemical precursor of GABA and can be converted into GABA by the actions of aldehyde reductase (ALR) and aldehyde dehydrogenase (ALDH) with γ-aminobutyraldehyde (GABAL) as a metabolic intermediate.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] It is the most abundant amino acid in the apoplast of tomatoes.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Evidence also suggests a role in cell signalling in plants.
[src:neurotransmitters/gamma-aminobutyric-acid] Recently, a new enzyme technology has been developed to enhance the GABA content of protein-rich seeds such as Andean lupine or tarwi (*Lupinus mutabilis*) and varieties of quinoa (*Chenopodium quinoa*) and its relative, cañahua (*Chenopodium pallidicaule*).
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Biochemical receptors for glutamate fall into two major classes, known as ionotropic glutamate receptors and metabotropic glutamate receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] The ionotropic glutamate receptors consist of AMPA receptors, NMDA receptors, and kainate receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] The metabotropic glutamate receptors consist of eight different individual receptors, being split into group I, group II, and group III.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Many synapses use multiple types of glutamate receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] AMPA receptors are ionotropic receptors specialized for fast excitation: in many synapses they produce excitatory electrical responses in their targets a fraction of a millisecond after being stimulated.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] NMDA receptors are also ionotropic, but they differ from AMPA receptors in being permeable, when activated, to calcium.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Their properties make them particularly important for learning and memory.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Metabotropic receptors act through second messenger systems to create slow, sustained effects on their targets.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Because of its role in synaptic plasticity, glutamate is involved in cognitive functions such as learning and memory in the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] The form of plasticity known as long-term potentiation takes place at glutamatergic synapses in the hippocampus, neocortex, and other parts of the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Glutamate works not only as a point-to-point transmitter, but also through spill-over synaptic crosstalk between synapses in which summation of glutamate released from a neighboring synapse creates extrasynaptic signaling/volume transmission.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] In addition, glutamate plays important roles in the regulation of growth cones and synaptogenesis during brain development.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Glutamate is a very major constituent of a wide variety of proteins; consequently it is one of the most abundant amino acids in the human body.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Glutamate is formally classified as a non-essential amino acid, because it can be synthesized (in sufficient quantities for health) from α-ketoglutaric acid, which is produced as part of the citric acid cycle by a series of reactions whose starting point is citrate.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Glutamate cannot cross the blood–brain barrier unassisted, but it is actively transported out of the nervous system by a high affinity transport system, which maintains its concentration in brain fluids at a fairly constant level.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Glutamate is synthesized in the central nervous system from glutamine as part of the glutamate–glutamine cycle by the enzyme glutaminase.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] This can occur in the presynaptic neuron or in neighboring glial cells.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Glutamate itself serves as metabolic precursor for the neurotransmitter GABA, via the action of the enzyme glutamate decarboxylase.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Glutamate exerts its effects by binding to and activating cell surface receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] In mammals, four families of glutamate receptors have been identified, known as AMPA receptors, kainate receptors, NMDA receptors, and metabotropic glutamate receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] The first three families are ionotropic, meaning that when activated they open membrane channels that allow ions to pass through.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] The metabotropic family are G protein-coupled receptors, meaning that they exert their effects via a complex second messenger system.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Glutamate transporters, EAAT and VGLUT, are found in neuronal and glial membranes.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] They rapidly remove glutamate from the extracellular space.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] In brain injury or disease, they often work in reverse, and excess glutamate can accumulate outside cells.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] This process causes calcium ions to enter cells via NMDA receptor channels, leading to neuronal damage and eventual cell death, and is called excitotoxicity.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Excitotoxicity due to excessive glutamate release and impaired uptake occurs as part of the ischemic cascade and is associated with stroke, autism, some forms of intellectual disability, and diseases such as amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, lathyrism, and Alzheimer's disease.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] In contrast, decreased glutamate release is observed under conditions of classical phenylketonuria leading to developmental disruption of glutamate receptor expression.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Glutamic acid has been implicated in epileptic seizures.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Microinjection of glutamic acid into neurons produces spontaneous depolarisations around one second apart, and this firing pattern is similar to what is known as paroxysmal depolarizing shift in epileptic attacks.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] This change in the resting membrane potential at seizure foci could cause spontaneous opening of voltage-activated calcium channels, leading to glutamic acid release and further depolarization.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Rather, ctenophores have functionally distinct types of ionotropic glutamate receptors, such that activation of these receptors may trigger muscle contraction and other responses.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Sponges do not have a nervous system, but also make use of glutamate for cell-to-cell signalling.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Sponges possess metabotropic glutamate receptors, and application of glutamate to a sponge can trigger a whole-body response that sponges use to rid themselves of contaminants.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] The genome of *Trichoplax*, a primitive organism that also lacks a nervous system, contains numerous metabotropic glutamate receptors, but their function is not yet known.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Glutamate is the primary excitatory neurotransmitter in the insect neuromuscular junction.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Glutamate binds to postsynaptic iGluRs, opening ion channels and causing muscle depolarization, and initiating fast contraction.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Specific iGluR subunits (e.g., GluRIIA, GluRIIB) and auxiliary proteins (Neto) are essential for assembling and anchoring these receptors at the synapse, ensuring proper signal transmission.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] In arthropods and nematodes, glutamate stimulates glutamate-gated chloride channels.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] The β subunits of the receptor respond with very high affinity to glutamate and glycine.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Targeting these receptors has been the therapeutic goal of anthelmintic therapy using avermectins.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Avermectins target the alpha subunit of glutamate-gated chloride channels with high affinity.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] These receptors have also been described in arthropods, such as *Drosophila melanogaster* and *Lepeophtheirus salmonis*.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Irreversible activation of these receptors with avermectins results in hyperpolarization at synapses and neuromuscular junctions resulting in flaccid paralysis and death of nematodes and arthropods.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] The first suggestion that glutamate might function as a transmitter came from T.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Hayashi in 1952, who was motivated by the finding that injections of glutamate into the cerebral ventricles of dogs could cause them to have seizures.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Other support for this idea soon appeared, but the majority of physiologists were skeptical, for a variety of theoretical and empirical reasons.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] One of the most common reasons for skepticism was the universality of glutamate's excitatory effects in the central nervous system, which seemed inconsistent with the specificity expected of a neurotransmitter.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] Other reasons for skepticism included a lack of known antagonists and the absence of a known mechanism for inactivation.
[src:neurotransmitters/glutamate-neurotransmitter] A series of discoveries during the 1970s resolved most of these doubts, and by 1980 the compelling nature of the evidence was almost universally recognized.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] A **neurotransmitter** is a signaling molecule secreted by a neuron to affect another cell across a synapse.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] The cell receiving the signal, or target cell, may be another neuron, but could also be a gland or muscle cell.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Neurotransmitters are released from synaptic vesicles into the synaptic cleft where they are able to interact with neurotransmitter receptors on the target cell.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Some neurotransmitters are also stored in large dense core vesicles.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] The neurotransmitter's effect on the target cell is determined by the receptor it binds to.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Many neurotransmitters are synthesized from simple and plentiful precursors such as amino acids, which are readily available and often require a small number of biosynthetic steps for conversion.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Neurotransmitters are essential to the function of complex neural systems.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] The exact number of unique neurotransmitters in humans is unknown, but more than 100 have been identified.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Common neurotransmitters include glutamate, GABA, acetylcholine, glycine, dopamine and norepinephrine.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Neurotransmitters are generally synthesized in neurons and are made up of, or derived from, precursor molecules that are found abundantly in the cell.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Classes of neurotransmitters include amino acids, monoamines, and peptides.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Monoamines are synthesized by altering a single amino acid.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] For example, the precursor of serotonin is the amino acid tryptophan.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Peptide neurotransmitters, or neuropeptides, are protein transmitters which are larger than the classical small-molecule neurotransmitters and are often released together to elicit a modulatory effect.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Purine neurotransmitters, like ATP, are derived from nucleic acids.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Metabolic products such as nitric oxide and carbon monoxide have also been reported to act like neurotransmitters.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Neurotransmitters are generally stored in synaptic vesicles, clustered close to the cell membrane at the axon terminal of the presynaptic neuron.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] However, some neurotransmitters, like the metabolic gases carbon monoxide and nitric oxide, are synthesized and released immediately following an action potential without ever being stored in vesicles.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Generally, a neurotransmitter is released via exocytosis at the presynaptic terminal in response to an electrical signal called an action potential in the presynaptic neuron.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] However, low-level "baseline" release also occurs without electrical stimulation.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Neurotransmitters are released into and diffuse across the synaptic cleft, where they bind to specific receptors on the membrane of the postsynaptic neuron.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] After being released into the synaptic cleft, neurotransmitters diffuse across the synapse where they are able to interact with receptors on the target cell.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] The effect of the neurotransmitter is dependent on the identity of the target cell's receptors present at the synapse.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Depending on the receptor, binding of neurotransmitters may cause excitation, inhibition, or modulation of the postsynaptic neuron.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] In order to avoid continuous activation of receptors on the post-synaptic or target cell, neurotransmitters must be removed from the synaptic cleft.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Enzyme degradation – proteins called enzymes break the neurotransmitters down.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Reuptake – neurotransmitters are reabsorbed into the pre-synaptic neuron.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Transporters, or membrane transport proteins, pump neurotransmitters from the synaptic cleft back into axon terminals (the presynaptic neuron) where they are stored for reuse.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] For example, acetylcholine is eliminated by having its acetyl group cleaved by the enzyme acetylcholinesterase; the remaining choline is then taken in and recycled by the pre-synaptic neuron to synthesize more acetylcholine.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Other neurotransmitters are able to diffuse away from their targeted synaptic junctions and are eliminated from the body via the kidneys, or destroyed in the liver.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Each neurotransmitter has very specific degradation pathways at regulatory points, which may be targeted by the body's regulatory system or medication.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Cocaine blocks a dopamine transporter responsible for the reuptake of dopamine.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Without the transporter, dopamine diffuses much more slowly from the synaptic cleft and continues to activate the dopamine receptors on the target cell.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Until the early 20th century, scientists assumed that the majority of synaptic communication in the brain was electrical.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] However, through histological examinations by Ramón y Cajal, a 20 to 40 nm gap between neurons, known today as the synaptic cleft, was discovered.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] The presence of such a gap suggested communication via chemical messengers traversing the synaptic cleft, and in 1921 German pharmacologist Otto Loewi confirmed that neurons can communicate by releasing chemicals.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Through a series of experiments involving the vagus nerves of frogs, Loewi was able to manually slow the heart rate of frogs by controlling the amount of saline solution present around the vagus nerve.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Upon completion of this experiment, Loewi asserted that sympathetic regulation of cardiac function can be mediated through changes in chemical concentrations.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Furthermore, Otto Loewi is credited with discovering acetylcholine (ACh) – the first known neurotransmitter.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Release and response: When the neuron is activated, the chemical must be released and elicit a response in target cells or neurons.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Experimental response: Application of the chemical directly to the target cells should produce the same response observed when the chemical is naturally released from neurons.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Removal mechanism: There must be a mechanism in place to remove the neurotransmitter from its site of action once its signaling role is complete.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] The anatomical localization of neurotransmitters is typically determined using immunocytochemical techniques, which identify the location of either the transmitter substances themselves or of the enzymes that are involved in their synthesis.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Immunocytochemical techniques have also revealed that many transmitters, particularly the neuropeptides, are co-localized, that is, a neuron may release more than one transmitter from its synaptic terminal.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Various techniques and experiments such as staining, stimulating, and collecting can be used to identify neurotransmitters throughout the central nervous system.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Neurons communicate with each other through synapses, specialized contact points where neurotransmitters transmit signals.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] When an action potential reaches the presynaptic terminal, voltage-gated calcium channels open, allowing calcium ions to enter the terminal.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] This calcium influx triggers the fusion of synaptic vesicles with the presynaptic membrane, leading to the release of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] These neurotransmitters then bind to receptors on the postsynaptic membrane, influencing the receiving neuron in either an inhibitory or excitatory manner.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] If the overall excitatory influences outweigh the inhibitory influences, the receiving neuron may generate its own action potential, continuing the transmission of information to the next neuron in the network.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] This process allows for the flow of information and the formation of complex neural networks.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] A neurotransmitter may have an excitatory, inhibitory or modulatory effect on the target cell.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] The effect is determined by the receptors the neurotransmitter interacts with at the post-synaptic membrane.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Neurotransmitters influence trans-membrane ion flow either to increase (excitatory) or to decrease (inhibitory) the probability that the cell with which it comes in contact will produce an action potential.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Synapses containing receptors with excitatory effects are called Type I synapses, while Type II synapses contain receptors with inhibitory effects.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Thus, despite the wide variety of synapses, they all convey only these two types of messages.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] The two types have different appearances and primarily act on different parts of neurons.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Receptors with modulatory effects are spread throughout all synaptic membranes and binding of neurotransmitters sets in motion signaling cascades that help the cell regulate its function.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Binding of neurotransmitters to receptors with modulatory effects can have many results.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] For example, it may increase or decrease in sensitivity to future stimuli by recruiting more or fewer receptors to the synaptic membrane.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Type I (excitatory) synapses are typically located on the shafts or the spines of dendrites, whereas type II (inhibitory) synapses are typically located on the cell body.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] In addition, Type I synapses have round synaptic vesicles, whereas the vesicles of type II synapses are flattened.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] The material on the presynaptic and post-synaptic membranes is denser in a Type I synapse than it is in a Type II, and the Type I synaptic cleft is wider.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Finally, the active zone on a Type I synapse is larger than that on a Type II synapse.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] The different locations of Type I and Type II synapses divide a neuron into two zones: an excitatory dendritic tree and an inhibitory cell body.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] From an inhibitory perspective, excitation comes in over the dendrites and spreads to the axon hillock to trigger an action potential.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] If the message is to be stopped, it is best stopped by applying inhibition on the cell body, close to the axon hillock, where the action potential originates.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Another way to conceptualize excitatory–inhibitory interaction is to picture excitation overcoming inhibition.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] If the cell body is normally in an inhibited state, the only way to generate an action potential at the axon hillock is to reduce the cell body's inhibition.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] In this "open the gates" strategy, the excitatory message is like a racehorse ready to run down the track, but first, the inhibitory starting gate must be removed.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] As explained above, the only direct action of a neurotransmitter is to activate a receptor.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Therefore, the effects of a neurotransmitter system depend on the connections of the neurons that use the transmitter, and the chemical properties of the receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] There are many different ways to classify neurotransmitters.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] They are commonly classified into amino acids, monoamines and peptides.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] In addition, over 100 neuroactive peptides have been found, and new ones are discovered regularly.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Many of these are co-released along with a small-molecule transmitter.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Nevertheless, in some cases, a peptide is the primary transmitter at a synapse.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Beta-Endorphin is a relatively well-known example of a peptide neurotransmitter because it engages in highly specific interactions with opioid receptors in the central nervous system.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Single ions (such as synaptically released zinc) are also considered neurotransmitters by some, as well as some gaseous molecules such as nitric oxide (NO), carbon monoxide (CO), and hydrogen sulfide (H2S).
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] The gases are produced in the neural cytoplasm and are immediately diffused through the cell membrane into the extracellular fluid and into nearby cells to stimulate production of second messengers.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Soluble gas neurotransmitters are difficult to study because they act rapidly and are immediately broken down, existing for only a few seconds.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] The most prevalent transmitter is glutamate, which is excitatory at well over 90% of the synapses in the human brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] The next most prevalent is gamma-Aminobutyric Acid, or GABA, which is inhibitory at more than 90% of the synapses that do not use glutamate.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Although other transmitters are used in fewer synapses, they may be very important functionally: the great majority of psychoactive drugs exert their effects by altering the actions of some neurotransmitter systems, often acting through transmitters other than glutamate or GABA.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Addictive drugs such as cocaine and amphetamines exert their effects primarily on the dopamine system.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] The addictive opiate drugs act primarily as functional analogs of opioid peptides, which, in turn, regulate dopamine levels.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Neurons expressing certain types of neurotransmitters sometimes form distinct systems, where activation of the system affects large volumes of the brain, called volume transmission.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Major neurotransmitter systems include the noradrenaline (norepinephrine) system, the dopamine system, the serotonin system, and the cholinergic system, among others.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Trace amines have a modulatory effect on neurotransmission in monoamine pathways (i.e., dopamine, norepinephrine, and serotonin pathways) throughout the brain via signaling through trace amine-associated receptor 1.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Understanding how drugs affect neurotransmitters constitutes a major area of research in neuroscience.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Many neuroscientists believe that these studies can improve understanding of the neural circuits involved in neurological and psychiatric disorders, and may contribute to the development of more effective treatments, as well as strategies for prevention and, potentially, cures.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Drugs can influence behavior by altering neurotransmitter activity in the nervous system.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Some drugs affect neurotransmitter synthesis by altering the activity of the enzymes involved in their production.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] When neurotransmitter synthesis is inhibited, the amount of neurotransmitter available for release decreases, thus reducing neurotransmitter activity.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Other drugs act by stimulating or blocking the release of specific neurotransmitters.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Some drugs also interfere with neurotransmitter storage by causing synaptic vesicles to leak, thereby reducing the amount of neurotransmitter released into the synapse.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Drugs that prevent a neurotransmitter from binding to its receptor are known as receptor antagonists.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] For example, antipsychotic drugs such as haloperidol, chlorpromazine, and clozapine act primarily as antagonists at dopamine receptors in the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] In contrast, receptor agonists bind to receptors and mimic the effects of endogenous neurotransmitters.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] An example is morphine, an opioid receptor agonist that mimics the actions of endogenous opioid peptides such as β-endorphin to relieve pain.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Other drugs prolong the activity of neurotransmitters after their release by blocking neurotransmitter reuptake or inhibiting enzymes responsible for neurotransmitter degradation.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Finally, some drugs interfere with the generation or propagation of action potentials by blocking ion channels involved in neuronal signaling.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] For example, tetrodotoxin blocks voltage-gated sodium channels, thereby preventing neural conduction in both the central and peripheral nervous systems; as a result, tetrodotoxin is highly toxic and can be lethal.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Drugs targeting the neurotransmitter of major systems affect the whole system, which can explain the complexity of action of some drugs.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Cocaine, for example, blocks the re-uptake of dopamine back into the presynaptic neuron, leaving the neurotransmitter molecules in the synaptic gap for an extended period of time.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Since the dopamine remains in the synapse longer, the neurotransmitter continues to bind to the receptors on the postsynaptic neuron, eliciting a pleasurable emotional response.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Physical addiction to cocaine may result from prolonged exposure to excess dopamine in the synapses, which leads to the downregulation of some post-synaptic receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] After the effects of the drug wear off, an individual can become depressed due to decreased probability of the neurotransmitter binding to a receptor.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] AMPT prevents the conversion of tyrosine to L-DOPA, the precursor to dopamine; reserpine prevents dopamine storage within vesicles; and deprenyl inhibits monoamine oxidase (MAO)-B and thus increases dopamine levels.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] An agonist is a chemical capable of binding to a receptor, such as a neurotransmitter receptor, and initiating the same reaction typically produced by the binding of the endogenous substance.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] An agonist of a neurotransmitter will thus initiate the same receptor response as the transmitter.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] In neurons, an agonist drug may activate neurotransmitter receptors either directly or indirectly.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Direct-binding agonists can be further characterized as full agonists, partial agonists, inverse agonists.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Direct agonists act similar to a neurotransmitter by binding directly to its associated receptor site(s), which may be located on the presynaptic neuron or postsynaptic neuron, or both.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Nicotine, a compound found in tobacco, is a direct agonist of most nicotinic acetylcholine receptors, mainly located in cholinergic neurons.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Opiates, such as morphine, heroin, hydrocodone, oxycodone, codeine, and methadone, are μ-opioid receptor agonists; this action mediates their euphoriant and pain relieving properties.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Indirect agonists increase the binding of neurotransmitters at their target receptors by stimulating the release or preventing the reuptake of neurotransmitters.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Some indirect agonists trigger neurotransmitter release and prevent neurotransmitter reuptake.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Indirect-acting antagonist- drugs that inhibit the release/production of neurotransmitters (e.g., Reserpine).
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] An antagonist is a drug that binds to a receptor without activating it, meaning it has no intrinsic activity.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] By occupying the receptor, it blocks or reduces the effect of an agonist, such as a drug, hormone, or neurotransmitter, that would normally bind to and activate the receptor.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Antagonists are often described as receptor “blockers” and may be classified as **competitive** or **irreversible**.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] A competitive antagonist competes with an agonist for binding to the receptor.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] As the concentration of the antagonist increases, agonist binding is progressively inhibited, resulting in a decrease in the physiological response.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] A high concentration of an antagonist can completely inhibit the response.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] This inhibition can be reversed by increasing the agonist concentration, since the agonist and antagonist compete for binding to the receptor.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Competitive antagonists, therefore, can be characterized as shifting the dose–response relationship for the agonist to the right.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] In the presence of a competitive antagonist, it takes an increased concentration of the agonist to produce the same response observed in the absence of the antagonist.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] An irreversible antagonist binds so strongly to the receptor that it renders the receptor unavailable for binding to the agonist.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Irreversible antagonists may even form covalent chemical bonds with the receptor.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] In either case, if the concentration of the irreversible antagonist is high enough, the number of unbound receptors remaining for agonist binding may be so low that even high concentrations of the agonist do not produce the maximum biological response.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] The following sections describe how imbalances or dysfunction in specific neurotransmitters—dopamine, serotonin, and glutamate—have been tentatively linked to various mental or neurological disorders.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] For example, problems in producing dopamine (mainly in the substantia nigra) can result in Parkinson's disease, a disorder that affects a person's ability to move as they want to, resulting in stiffness, tremors or shaking, and other symptoms.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Some studies suggest that having too little or too much dopamine or problems using dopamine in the thinking and feeling regions of the brain may play a role in disorders like schizophrenia or attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD).
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Dopamine is also involved in addiction and drug use, as most recreational drugs cause an influx of dopamine in the brain (especially opioid and methamphetamines) that produces a pleasurable feeling, which is why users constantly crave drugs.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Similarly, after some research suggested that drugs that block the recycling, or reuptake, of serotonin seemed to help some people diagnosed with depression, it was theorized that people with depression might have lower-than-normal serotonin levels.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Though widely popularized, this theory was not borne out in subsequent research.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Therefore, selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) are used to increase the amounts of serotonin in synapses.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Furthermore, problems with producing or using glutamate have been suggestively and tentatively linked to many mental disorders, including autism, obsessive–compulsive disorder (OCD), schizophrenia, and depression.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Having too much glutamate has been linked to neurological diseases such as Parkinson's disease, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's disease, stroke, and ALS (amyotrophic lateral sclerosis).
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Generally, there are no scientifically established "norms" for appropriate levels or "balances" of different neurotransmitters.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] In most cases, it is practically impossible to measure neurotransmitter levels in the brain or body at any given moment.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Neurotransmitters regulate each other's release, and weak consistent imbalances in this mutual regulation were linked to temperament in healthy people.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] However, significant imbalances or disruptions in neurotransmitter systems are associated with various diseases and mental disorders, including Parkinson's disease, depression, insomnia, Attention Deficit Hyperactivity Disorder (ADHD), anxiety, memory loss, dramatic weight changes, and addictions.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Some of these conditions are also related to neurotransmitter switching, a phenomenon where neurons change the type of neurotransmitters they release.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Chronic physical or emotional stress can be a contributor to neurotransmitter system changes.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Genetics also plays a role in neurotransmitter activities.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Apart from recreational use, medications that directly and indirectly interact with one or more transmitter or its receptor are commonly prescribed for psychiatric and psychological issues.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Notably, drugs interacting with serotonin and norepinephrine are prescribed to patients with problems such as depression and anxiety—though the notion that there is much solid medical evidence to support such interventions has been widely criticized.
[src:neurotransmitters/neurotransmitter] Studies shown that dopamine imbalance has an influence on multiple sclerosis and other neurological disorders.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The general function of norepinephrine is to mobilize the brain and body for action.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Norepinephrine release is lowest during sleep, rises during wakefulness, and reaches much higher levels during situations of stress or danger, in the so-called fight-or-flight response.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] In the brain, norepinephrine increases arousal and alertness, promotes vigilance, enhances formation and retrieval of memory, and focuses attention; it also increases restlessness and anxiety.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] In the rest of the body, norepinephrine increases heart rate and blood pressure, triggers the release of glucose from energy stores, increases blood flow to skeletal muscle, reduces blood flow to the gastrointestinal system, and inhibits voiding of the bladder and gastrointestinal motility.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] In the brain, noradrenaline is produced in nuclei that are small yet exert powerful effects on other brain areas.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The most important of these nuclei is the locus coeruleus, located in the pons.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Outside the brain, norepinephrine is used as a neurotransmitter by sympathetic ganglia located near the spinal cord or in the abdomen, as well as Merkel cells located in the skin.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] It is also released directly into the bloodstream by the adrenal glands.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Regardless of how and where it is released, norepinephrine acts on target cells by binding to and activating adrenergic receptors located on the cell surface.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] A variety of medically important drugs work by altering the actions of noradrenaline systems.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Noradrenaline itself is widely used as an injectable drug for the treatment of critically low blood pressure.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Stimulants often increase, enhance, or otherwise act as agonists of norepinephrine.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Drugs such as cocaine and methylphenidate act as reuptake inhibitors of norepinephrine, as do some antidepressants, such as those in the SNRI class.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] One of the more notable drugs in the stimulant class is amphetamine, which acts as a dopamine and norepinephrine analog, reuptake inhibitor, as well as an agent that increases the amount of global catecholamine signaling throughout the nervous system by reversing transporters in the synapses.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Alpha blockers, which counter the effects of noradrenaline on alpha-adrenergic receptors, are occasionally used to treat hypertension and psychiatric conditions.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Alpha-2 agonists often have a sedating and antihypertensive effect and are commonly used as anesthesia enhancers in surgery, as well as in treatment of drug or alcohol dependence.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] For reasons that are still unclear, some Alpha-2 agonists, such as guanfacine, have also been shown to be effective in the treatment of anxiety disorders and ADHD.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Many important psychiatric drugs exert strong effects on noradrenaline systems in the brain, resulting in effects that may be helpful or harmful.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Norepinephrine is a catecholamine and a phenethylamine.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Its structure differs from that of epinephrine only in that epinephrine has a methyl group attached to its nitrogen, whereas the methyl group is replaced by a hydrogen atom in norepinephrine.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The prefix *nor-* is derived as an abbreviation of the word "normal", used to indicate a demethylated compound.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Norepinephrine consists of a catechol moiety (a benzene ring with two adjoining hydroxyl groups in the *meta*-*para* position), and an ethylamine side chain consisting of a hydroxyl group bonded in the benzylic position.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] While the conversion of tyrosine to dopamine occurs predominantly in the cytoplasm, the conversion of dopamine to norepinephrine by dopamine β-monooxygenase occurs predominantly inside neurotransmitter vesicles.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Thus the direct precursor of norepinephrine is dopamine, which is synthesized indirectly from the essential amino acid phenylalanine or the non-essential amino acid tyrosine.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] These amino acids are found in nearly every protein and, as such, are provided by ingestion of protein-containing food, with tyrosine being the most common.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Phenylalanine is converted into tyrosine by the enzyme phenylalanine hydroxylase, with molecular oxygen (O2) and tetrahydrobiopterin as cofactors.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Tyrosine is converted into L-DOPA by the enzyme tyrosine hydroxylase, with tetrahydrobiopterin, O2, and probably ferrous iron (Fe2+) as cofactors.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Conversion of tyrosine to L-DOPA is inhibited by Metyrosine, a tyrosine analog.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] L-DOPA is converted into dopamine by the enzyme aromatic L-amino acid decarboxylase (also known as DOPA decarboxylase), with pyridoxal phosphate as a cofactor.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Dopamine is then converted into norepinephrine by the enzyme dopamine β-monooxygenase (formerly known as *dopamine β-hydroxylase*), with O2 and ascorbic acid as cofactors.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Norepinephrine itself can further be converted into epinephrine by the enzyme phenylethanolamine *N*-methyltransferase with *S*-adenosyl-L-methionine as cofactor.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] In mammals, norepinephrine is rapidly degraded to various metabolites.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The initial step in the breakdown can be catalyzed by either of the enzymes monoamine oxidase (mainly monoamine oxidase A) or COMT.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] From there, the breakdown can proceed by a variety of pathways.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The principal end products are either Vanillylmandelic acid or a conjugated form of MHPG, both of which are thought to be biologically inactive and are excreted in the urine.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Like many other biologically active substances, norepinephrine exerts its effects by binding to and activating receptors located on the surface of cells.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Two broad families of norepinephrine receptors have been identified, known as alpha and beta-adrenergic receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Alpha receptors are divided into subtypes α1 and α2; beta receptors into subtypes β1, β2, and β3.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] All of these function as G protein-coupled receptors, meaning that they exert their effects via a complex second messenger system.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Alpha-2 receptors usually have inhibitory effects, but many are located pre-synaptically (i.e., on the surface of the cells that release norepinephrine), so the net effect of alpha-2 activation is often a decrease in the amount of norepinephrine released.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Alpha-1 receptors and all three types of beta receptors usually have excitatory effects.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Inside the brain norepinephrine functions as a neurotransmitter and neuromodulator, and is controlled by a set of mechanisms common to all monoamine neurotransmitters.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] After synthesis, norepinephrine is transported from the cytosol into synaptic vesicles by the vesicular monoamine transporter (VMAT).
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] VMAT can be inhibited by Reserpine causing a decrease in neurotransmitter stores.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Norepinephrine is stored in these vesicles until it is ejected into the synaptic cleft, typically after an action potential causes the vesicles to release their contents directly into the synaptic cleft through a process called exocytosis.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Once in the synapse, norepinephrine binds to and activates receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] After an action potential, the norepinephrine molecules quickly become unbound from their receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] They are then absorbed back into the presynaptic cell, via reuptake mediated primarily by the norepinephrine transporter (NET).
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Once back in the cytosol, norepinephrine can either be broken down by monoamine oxidase or repackaged into vesicles by VMAT, making it available for future release.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Norepinephrine is the main neurotransmitter used by the sympathetic nervous system, which consists of about two dozen sympathetic chain ganglia located next to the spinal cord, plus a set of prevertebral ganglia located in the chest and abdomen.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] These sympathetic ganglia are connected to numerous organs, including the eyes, salivary glands, heart, lungs, liver, gallbladder, stomach, intestines, kidneys, urinary bladder, reproductive organs, muscles, skin, and adrenal glands.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Sympathetic activation of the adrenal glands causes the part called the adrenal medulla to release norepinephrine (as well as epinephrine) into the bloodstream, from which, functioning as a hormone, it gains further access to a wide variety of tissues.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Broadly speaking, the effect of norepinephrine on each target organ is to modify its state in a way that makes it more conducive to active body movement, often at a cost of increased energy use and increased wear and tear.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] This can be contrasted with the acetylcholine-mediated effects of the parasympathetic nervous system, which modifies most of the same organs into a state more conducive to rest, recovery, and digestion of food, and usually less costly in terms of energy expenditure.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Noradrenaline and ATP are sympathetic co-transmitters.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] It is found that the endocannabinoid anandamide and the cannabinoid WIN 55,212-2 can modify the overall response to sympathetic nerve stimulation, which indicates that prejunctional CB1 receptors mediate the sympatho-inhibitory action.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Thus cannabinoids can inhibit both the noradrenergic and purinergic components of sympathetic neurotransmission.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The noradrenergic neurons in the brain form a neurotransmitter system, that, when activated, exerts effects on large areas of the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The effects are manifested in alertness, arousal, and readiness for action.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Noradrenergic neurons (i.e., neurons whose primary neurotransmitter is norepinephrine) are comparatively few in number, and their cell bodies are confined to a few relatively small brain areas, but they send projections to many other brain areas and exert powerful effects on their targets.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] These noradrenergic cell groups were first mapped in 1964 by Annica Dahlström and Kjell Fuxe, who assigned them labels starting with the letter "A" (for "aminergic").
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] In their scheme, areas A1 through A7 contain the neurotransmitter norepinephrine (A8 through A14 contain dopamine).
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Noradrenergic cell group A1 is located in the caudal ventrolateral part of the medulla, and plays a role in the control of body fluid metabolism.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Noradrenergic cell group A2 is located in a brainstem area called the solitary nucleus; these cells have been implicated in a variety of responses, including control of food intake and responses to stress.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Cell groups A5 and A7 project mainly to the spinal cord.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The most important source of norepinephrine in the brain is the locus coeruleus, which contains noradrenergic cell group A6 and adjoins cell group A4.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The locus coeruleus is quite small in absolute terms—in primates, it is estimated to contain around 15,000 neurons, less than one-millionth of the neurons in the brain—but it sends projections to every major part of the brain and also to the spinal cord.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The level of activity in the locus coeruleus correlates broadly with vigilance and speed of reaction.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] LC activity is low during sleep and drops to virtually nothing during the REM (dreaming) state.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] It runs at a baseline level during wakefulness, but increases temporarily when a person is presented with any sort of stimulus that draws attention.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Unpleasant stimuli such as pain, difficulty breathing, bladder distension, heat or cold generate larger increases.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Extremely unpleasant states such as intense fear or intense pain are associated with very high levels of LC activity.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Norepinephrine released by the locus coeruleus affects brain function in several ways.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] It enhances processing of sensory inputs, enhances attention, enhances formation and retrieval of both long-term and working memory, and enhances the ability of the brain to respond to inputs by changing the activity pattern in the prefrontal cortex and other areas.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The control of arousal level is strong enough that drug-induced suppression of the LC has a powerful sedating effect.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] There is a great similarity between situations that activate the locus coeruleus in the brain and situations that activate the sympathetic nervous system in the periphery: the LC essentially mobilizes the brain for action while the sympathetic system mobilizes the body.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] It has been argued that this similarity arises because both are to a large degree controlled by the same brain structures, particularly a part of the brainstem called the nucleus gigantocellularis.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Norepinephrine is also produced by Merkel cells which are part of the somatosensory system.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] It activates the afferent sensory neuron.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] A large number of important drugs exert their effects by interacting with norepinephrine systems in the brain or body.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Their uses include treatment of cardiovascular problems, shock, and a variety of psychiatric conditions.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] These drugs are divided into: sympathomimetic drugs which mimic or enhance at least some of the effects of norepinephrine released by the sympathetic nervous system; sympatholytic drugs, in contrast, block at least some of the effects.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Both of these are large groups with diverse uses, depending on exactly which effects are enhanced or blocked.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Norepinephrine itself is classified as a sympathomimetic drug: its effects when given by intravenous injection of increasing heart rate and force and constricting blood vessels make it very useful for treating medical emergencies that involve critically low blood pressure.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Surviving Sepsis Campaign recommended norepinephrine as first line agent in treating septic shock which is unresponsive to fluid resuscitation, supplemented by vasopressin and epinephrine.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Dopamine usage is restricted only to highly selected patients.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] These are sympatholytic drugs that block the effects of beta adrenergic receptors while having little or no effect on alpha receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] They are sometimes used to treat high blood pressure, atrial fibrillation, and congestive heart failure, but recent reviews have concluded that other types of drugs are usually superior for those purposes.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Beta blockers may be a viable choice for other cardiovascular conditions, though, including angina and Marfan syndrome.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] They are also widely used to treat glaucoma, most commonly in the form of eyedrops.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Because of their effects in reducing anxiety symptoms and tremor, they have sometimes been used by entertainers, public speakers, and athletes to reduce performance anxiety, although they are not medically approved for that purpose and are banned by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] However, the usefulness of beta blockers is limited by a range of serious side effects, including slowing of heart rate, a drop in blood pressure, asthma, and reactive hypoglycemia.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The negative effects can be particularly severe in people with diabetes.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] These are sympatholytic drugs that block the effects of adrenergic alpha receptors while having little or no effect on beta receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Drugs belonging to this group can have very different effects, however, depending on whether they primarily block alpha-1 receptors, alpha-2 receptors, or both.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Alpha-2 receptors, as described elsewhere in this article, are frequently located on norepinephrine-releasing neurons themselves and have inhibitory effects on them; consequently, blockage of alpha-2 receptors usually results in an increase in norepinephrine release.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Alpha-1 receptors are usually located on target cells and have excitatory effects on them; consequently, blockage of alpha-1 receptors usually results in blocking some of the effects of norepinephrine.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Drugs such as phentolamine that act on both types of receptors can produce a complex combination of both effects.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] In most cases when the term "alpha blocker" is used without qualification, it refers to a selective alpha-1 antagonist.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Selective alpha-1 blockers have a variety of uses.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Since one of their effects is to inhibit the contraction of the smooth muscle in the prostate, they are often used to treat symptoms of benign prostatic hyperplasia.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Alpha-blockers also likely help people pass their kidney stones.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Their effects on the central nervous system make them useful for treating generalized anxiety disorder, panic disorder, and posttraumatic stress disorder.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] They may, however, have significant side effects, including a drop in blood pressure.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Some antidepressants function partly as selective alpha-2 blockers, but the best-known drug in that class is yohimbine, which is extracted from the bark of the African yohimbe tree.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Yohimbine acts as a male potency enhancer, but its usefulness for that purpose is limited by serious side-effects including anxiety and insomnia.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Overdoses can cause a dangerous increase in blood pressure.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Yohimbine is banned in many countries, but in the United States, because it is extracted from a plant rather than chemically synthesized, it is sold over the counter as a nutritional supplement.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] These are sympathomimetic drugs that activate alpha-2 receptors or enhance their effects.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Because alpha-2 receptors are inhibitory and many are located presynaptically on norepinephrine-releasing cells, the net effect of these drugs is usually to reduce the amount of norepinephrine released.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Drugs in this group that are capable of entering the brain often have strong sedating effects, due to their inhibitory effects on the locus coeruleus.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Clonidine and guanfacine, for example, are used for the treatment of anxiety disorders and insomnia, and also as a sedative premedication for patients about to undergo surgery.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Xylazine, another drug in this group, is also a powerful sedative and is often used in combination with ketamine as a general anaesthetic for veterinary surgery—in the United States it has not been approved for use in humans.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] These are drugs whose primary effects are thought to be mediated by different neurotransmitter systems (dopamine for stimulants, serotonin for antidepressants), but many also increase levels of norepinephrine in the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Amphetamine, for example, is a stimulant that increases release of norepinephrine as well as dopamine.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Monoamine oxidase A inhibitors (MAO-A) are antidepressants that inhibit the metabolic degradation of norepinephrine as well as serotonin and dopamine.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] In some cases it is difficult to distinguish the norepinephrine-mediated effects from the effects related to other neurotransmitters.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] A number of important medical problems involve dysfunction of the norepinephrine system in the brain or body.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Hyperactivation of the sympathetic nervous system is not a recognized condition in itself, but it is a component of a number of conditions, as well as a possible consequence of taking sympathomimetic drugs.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] It causes a distinctive set of symptoms including aches and pains, rapid heartbeat, elevated blood pressure, sweating, palpitations, anxiety, headache, paleness, and a drop in blood glucose.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] If sympathetic activity is elevated for an extended time, it can cause weight loss and other stress-related body changes.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The list of conditions that can cause sympathetic hyperactivation includes severe brain injury, spinal cord damage, heart failure, high blood pressure, kidney disease, and various types of stress.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] A pheochromocytoma is a rarely occurring tumor of the adrenal medulla, caused either by genetic factors or certain types of cancer.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The consequence is a massive increase in the amount of norepinephrine and epinephrine released into the bloodstream.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The most obvious symptoms are those of sympathetic hyperactivation, including particularly a rise in blood pressure that can reach fatal levels.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The most effective treatment is surgical removal of the tumor.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Stress, to a physiologist, means any situation that threatens the continued stability of the body and its functions.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Stress affects a wide variety of body systems: the two most consistently activated are the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis and the norepinephrine system, including both the sympathetic nervous system and the locus coeruleus-centered system in the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Stressors of many types evoke increases in noradrenergic activity, which mobilizes the brain and body to meet the threat.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Chronic stress, if continued for a long time, can damage many parts of the body.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] A significant part of the damage is due to the effects of sustained norepinephrine release, because of norepinephrine's general function of directing resources away from maintenance, regeneration, and reproduction, and toward systems that are required for active movement.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The consequences can include slowing of growth (in children), sleeplessness, loss of libido, gastrointestinal problems, impaired disease resistance, slower rates of injury healing, depression, and increased vulnerability to addiction.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder is a neurodevelopmental condition involving problems with attention, hyperactivity, and impulsiveness.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] There is also substantial evidence that many people with ADHD show biomarkers involving altered norepinephrine processing.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Several drugs whose primary effects are on norepinephrine, including guanfacine, clonidine, and atomoxetine, have been tried as treatments for ADHD, and found to have effects comparable to those of stimulants.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Several conditions, including Parkinson's disease, diabetes, and so-called pure autonomic failure, can cause a loss of norepinephrine-secreting neurons in the sympathetic nervous system.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The symptoms are widespread, the most serious being a reduction in heart rate and an extreme drop in resting blood pressure, making it impossible for severely affected people to stand for more than a few seconds without fainting.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Treatment can involve dietary changes or drugs.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Norepinephrine prevents REM sleep, and lack of REM sleep increases noradrenaline secretion as a result of the locus coeruleus not ceasing producing it.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] It causes neurodegeneration if its loss is sustained for several days.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Norepinephrine has been reported to exist in a wide variety of animal species, including protozoa, placozoa and cnidaria (jellyfish and related species), but not in ctenophores (comb jellies), whose nervous systems differ greatly from those of other animals.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] It is generally present in deuterostomes (vertebrates, etc.), but in protostomes (arthropods, molluscs, flatworms, nematodes, annelids, etc.) it is replaced by octopamine, a closely related chemical with a closely related synthesis pathway.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] In insects, octopamine has alerting and activating functions that correspond (at least roughly) with the functions of norepinephrine in vertebrates.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] It has been argued that octopamine evolved to replace norepinephrine rather than *vice versa*; however, the nervous system of amphioxus (a primitive chordate) has been reported to contain octopamine but not norepinephrine, which presents difficulties for that hypothesis.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] The Belgian pharmacologist Zénon Bacq as well as Canadian and U.S. pharmacologists between 1934 and 1938 suggested that noradrenaline might be a sympathetic transmitter.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] In 1939, Hermann Blaschko and Peter Holtz independently identified the biosynthetic mechanism for norepinephrine in the vertebrate body.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] In 1945 Ulf von Euler published the first of a series of papers that established the role of norepinephrine as a neurotransmitter.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] He demonstrated the presence of norepinephrine in sympathetically innervated tissues and brain, and adduced evidence that it is the *sympathin* of Cannon and Rosenblueth.
[src:neurotransmitters/norepinephrine] Stanley Peart was the first to demonstrate the release of noradrenaline after the stimulation of sympathetic nerves.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Most of the body's serotonin—about 90%—is synthesized in the gastrointestinal tract by enterochromaffin cells, where it regulates intestinal movements.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] It is also produced in smaller amounts in the brainstem's raphe nuclei, the skin's Merkel cells, pulmonary neuroendocrine cells, and taste receptor cells of the tongue.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Once secreted, serotonin is taken up by platelets in the blood, which release it during clotting to promote vasoconstriction and platelet aggregation.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Around 8% of the body's serotonin is stored in platelets, and 1–2% is found in the CNS.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin acts as both a vasoconstrictor and vasodilator depending on concentration and context, influencing hemostasis and blood pressure regulation.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] It plays a role in stimulating myenteric neurons and enhancing gastrointestinal motility through uptake and release cycles in platelets and surrounding tissue.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Biochemically, serotonin is an indoleamine synthesized from tryptophan and metabolized primarily in the liver to 5-hydroxyindoleacetic acid (5-HIAA).
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin is targeted by several classes of antidepressants, including selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) and serotonin–norepinephrine reuptake inhibitors (SNRIs), which block reabsorption in the synapse to elevate its levels.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] It is found in nearly all bilateral animals, including insects, spiders and worms, and also occurs in fungi and plants.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] In plants and insect venom, it serves a defensive function by inducing pain.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin released by pathogenic amoebae may cause diarrhea in the human gut, while its presence in seeds and fruits is thought to stimulate digestion and facilitate seed dispersal.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Biochemically, the indoleamine molecule derives from the amino acid tryptophan, via the (rate-limiting) hydroxylation of the 5 position on the ring (forming the intermediate 5-hydroxytryptophan), and then decarboxylation to produce serotonin.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Preferable conformations are defined via ethylamine chain, resulting in six different conformations.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin crystallizes in P212121 chiral space group forming different hydrogen-bonding interactions between serotonin molecules via N-H...O and O-H...N intermolecular bonds.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin also forms several salts, including pharmaceutical formulation of serotonin adipate.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin is involved in numerous physiological processes, including sleep, thermoregulation, learning and memory, pain, (social) behavior, sexual activity, feeding, motor activity, neural development, and biological rhythms.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] In less complex animals, such as some invertebrates, serotonin regulates feeding and other processes.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] In plants serotonin synthesis seems to be associated with stress signals.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Despite its longstanding prominence in pharmaceutical advertising, the claim that low serotonin levels cause depression is not supported by scientific evidence.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin primarily acts through its receptors and its effects depend on which cells and tissues express these receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Metabolism involves first oxidation by monoamine oxidase to 5-hydroxyindoleacetaldehyde (5-HIAL).
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The rate-limiting step is hydride transfer from serotonin to the flavin cofactor.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] There follows oxidation by aldehyde dehydrogenase (ALDH) to 5-hydroxyindoleacetic acid (5-HIAA), the indole acetic-acid derivative.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The latter is then excreted by the kidneys.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The serotonin receptors are located on the cell membrane of nerve cells and other cell types in animals, and mediate the effects of serotonin as the endogenous ligand and of a broad range of pharmaceutical and psychedelic drugs.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Except for the serotonin 5-HT3 receptor, a ligand-gated ion channel, all other 5-HT receptors are G-protein-coupled receptors (also called seven-transmembrane, or heptahelical receptors) that activate an intracellular second messenger cascade.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The 5-HT5B receptor is present in rodents but not in humans.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] In addition to the serotonin receptors, serotonin is an agonist of the trace amine-associated receptor 1 (TAAR1) in some species.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] It is a weak TAAR1 partial agonist in rats, but is inactive at the TAAR1 in mice and humans.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The cryo-EM structures of the serotonin 5-HT2A receptor with serotonin, as well as with various serotonergic psychedelics, have been solved and published by Bryan L.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Protein serotonylation refers to the post-translational modification in which serotonin is covalently attached to glutamine residues on substrate proteins via a transamidation reaction catalyzed by TGM2.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonylation is a type of monoaminylation, which itself refers to the *overall class* of post-translational modifications involving monoamines.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] However, monoaminylation reactions are further classified by the individual monoamine reactant they describe (ie., serotonylation, dopaminylation, histaminylation).
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonylation has been reported for both histone and non-histone protein substrates, and thus represents a distinct neuroepigenetic and neuroproteomic regulatory mechanism with various implications in health and disease.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Since 2003, multiple studies have revealed the critical role of serotonylation in mediating a wide range of physiological processes, both in the nervous system and beyond.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonylation is known to contribute to several significant diseases, including neuropsychiatric disorders such as depression and schizophrenia, as well as a variety of cancers.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonylation is known to influence both tumorigenesis and cancer metastasis, and has been implicated in several types of cancer, including colorectal cancer, neuroendocrine prostate cancer, pancreatic cancer, hepatocellular carcinoma, and ependymomas (brain cancer).
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonergic action is terminated primarily via uptake of 5-HT from the synapse.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] This is accomplished through the specific monoamine transporter for 5-HT, SERT, on the presynaptic neuron.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Various agents can inhibit 5-HT reuptake, including cocaine, dextromethorphan (an antitussive), tricyclic antidepressants and selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs).
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] A 2006 study found that a significant portion of 5-HT's synaptic clearance is due to the selective activity of the plasma membrane monoamine transporter (PMAT) which actively transports the molecule across the membrane and back into the presynaptic cell.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] In contrast to the high affinity of SERT, the PMAT has been identified as a low-affinity transporter, with an apparent *K*m of 114 micromoles/l for serotonin, which is approximately 230 times higher than that of SERT.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] However, the PMAT, despite its relatively low serotonergic affinity, has a considerably higher transport "capacity" than SERT, "resulting in roughly comparable uptake efficiencies to SERT in heterologous expression systems".
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The study also suggests that the administration of SSRIs such as fluoxetine and sertraline may be associated with an inhibitory effect on PMAT activity when used at higher than normal dosages (IC50 test values used in trials were 3–4 fold higher than typical prescriptive dosage).
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The neurons of the raphe nuclei are the principal source of 5-HT release in the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] There are nine raphe nuclei, designated B1–B9, which contain the majority of serotonin-containing neurons (some scientists chose to group the *nuclei raphes lineares* into one nucleus), all of which are located along the midline of the brainstem, and centered on the reticular formation.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Axons from the neurons of the raphe nuclei form a neurotransmitter system reaching almost every part of the central nervous system.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Axons of neurons in the lower raphe nuclei terminate in the cerebellum and spinal cord, while the axons of the higher nuclei spread out in the entire brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] It is the dorsal part of the raphe nucleus that contains neurons projecting to the central nervous system.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin-releasing neurons in this area receive input from a large number of areas, notably from prefrontal cortex, lateral habenula, preoptic area, substantia nigra and amygdala.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] These neurons are thought to communicate the expectation of rewards in the near future, a quantity called state value in reinforcement learning.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The serotonin nuclei may also be divided into two main groups, the rostral and caudal containing three and four nuclei respectively.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The rostral group consists of the caudal linear nuclei (B8), the dorsal raphe nuclei (B6 and B7) and the median raphe nuclei (B5, B8 and B9), that project into multiple cortical and subcortical structures.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The caudal group consists of the nucleus raphe magnus (B3), raphe obscurus nucleus (B2), raphe pallidus nucleus (B1), and lateral medullary reticular formation, that project into the brainstem.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The serotonergic pathway is involved in sensorimotor function, with pathways projecting both into cortical (dorsal and median raphe nuclei), subcortical, and spinal areas involved in motor activity.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Pharmacological manipulation suggests that serotonergic activity increases with motor activity while firing rates of serotonergic neurons increase with intense visual stimuli.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Animal models suggest that kainate signaling negatively regulates serotonin actions in the retina, with possible implications for the control of the visual system.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The descending projections form a pathway that inhibits pain called the "descending inhibitory pathway" that may be relevant to a disorder such as fibromyalgia, migraine, and other pain disorders, and the efficacy of antidepressants in them.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonergic projections from the caudal nuclei are involved in regulating mood and emotion, and hypo- or hyper-serotonergic states may be involved in depression and sickness behavior.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin is released into the synapse, or space between neurons, and diffuses over a relatively wide gap (>20 nm) to activate 5-HT receptors located on the dendrites, cell bodies, and presynaptic terminals of adjacent neurons.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] When humans smell food, dopamine is released to increase the appetite.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] But, unlike in worms, serotonin does not increase anticipatory behaviour in humans; instead, the serotonin released while consuming activates 5-HT2C receptors on dopamine-producing cells.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] This halts their dopamine release, and thereby serotonin decreases appetite.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Drugs that block 5-HT2C receptors make the body unable to recognize when it is no longer hungry or otherwise in need of nutrients, and are associated with weight gain, especially in people with a low number of receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The expression of 5-HT2C receptors in the hippocampus follows a diurnal rhythm, just as the serotonin release in the ventromedial nucleus, which is characterised by a peak at morning when the motivation to eat is strongest.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] In macaques, alpha males have twice the level of serotonin in the brain as subordinate males and females (measured by the concentration of 5-HIAA in the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF)).
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Dominance status and CSF serotonin levels appear to be positively correlated.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] When dominant males were removed from such groups, subordinate males begin competing for dominance.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Once new dominance hierarchies were established, serotonin levels of the new dominant individuals also increased to double those in subordinate males and females.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The reason why serotonin levels are only high in dominant males, but not dominant females has not yet been established.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] In humans, levels of 5-HT1A receptor inhibition in the brain show negative correlation with aggression, and a mutation in the gene that codes for the 5-HT2A receptor may double the risk of suicide for those with that genotype.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin in the brain is not usually degraded after use, but is collected by serotonergic neurons through serotonin transporters on their cell surfaces.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Studies have revealed nearly 10% of total variance in anxiety-related personality depends on variations in the description of where, when and how many serotonin transporters the neurons should deploy.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin regulates gastrointestinal (GI) function.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The gut is surrounded by enterochromaffin cells, which release serotonin in response to food in the lumen.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] This makes the gut contract around the food.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Platelets in the veins draining the gut collect excess serotonin.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] There are often serotonin abnormalities in gastrointestinal disorders such as constipation and irritable bowel syndrome.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] If irritants are present in the food, the enterochromaffin cells release more serotonin to make the gut move faster, i.e., to cause diarrhea, so the gut is emptied of the noxious substance.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] If serotonin is released in the blood faster than the platelets can absorb it, the level of free serotonin in the blood is increased.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] This activates 5-HT3 receptors in the chemoreceptor trigger zone that stimulate vomiting.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Thus, drugs and toxins stimulate serotonin release from enterochromaffin cells in the gut wall which can induce emesis.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The enterochromaffin cells not only react to bad food but are also very sensitive to irradiation and cancer chemotherapy.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Drugs that block 5HT3 are very effective in controlling the nausea and vomiting produced by cancer treatment, and are considered the gold standard for this purpose.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The lung, including that of reptiles, contains specialized epithelial cells that occur as solitary cells or as clusters called neuroepithelial bodies or bronchial Kulchitsky cells or alternatively *K cells*.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] These are enterochromaffin cells that like those in the gut release serotonin.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Their function is probably vasoconstriction during hypoxia.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin is also produced by Merkel cells which are part of the somatosensory system.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] In mice and humans, alterations in serotonin levels and signalling have been shown to regulate bone mass.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Mice that lack brain serotonin have osteopenia, while mice that lack gut serotonin have high bone density.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] In humans, increased blood serotonin levels have been shown to be a significant negative predictor of low bone density.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin can also be synthesized, albeit at very low levels, in the bone cells.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] It mediates its actions on bone cells using three different receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Through 5-HT1B receptors, it negatively regulates bone mass, while it does so positively through 5-HT2B receptors and 5-HT2C receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] There is very delicate balance between physiological role of gut serotonin and its pathology.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Increase in the extracellular content of serotonin results in a complex relay of signals in the osteoblasts culminating in FoxO1/ Creb and ATF4 dependent transcriptional events.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Following the 2008 findings that gut serotonin regulates bone mass, the mechanistic investigations into what regulates serotonin synthesis from the gut in the regulation of bone mass have started.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Piezo1 has been shown to sense RNA in the gut and relay this information through serotonin synthesis to the bone by acting as a sensor of single-stranded RNA (ssRNA) governing 5-HT production.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Intestinal epithelium-specific deletion of mouse *Piezo1* profoundly disturbed gut peristalsis, impeded experimental colitis, and suppressed serum 5-HT levels.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Because of systemic 5-HT deficiency, conditional knockout of *Piezo1* increased bone formation.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Notably, fecal ssRNA was identified as a natural Piezo1 ligand, and ssRNA-stimulated 5-HT synthesis from the gut was evoked in a MyD88/TRIF-independent manner.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Colonic infusion of RNase A suppressed gut motility and increased bone mass.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] These findings suggest gut ssRNA as a master determinant of systemic 5-HT levels, indicating the ssRNA-Piezo1 axis as a potential prophylactic target for treatment of bone and gut disorders.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Studies in 2008, 2010 and 2019 have opened the potential for serotonin research to treat bone mass disorders.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Since serotonin signals resource availability it is not surprising that it affects organ development.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Many human and animal studies have shown that nutrition in early life can influence, in adulthood, such things as body fatness, blood lipids, blood pressure, atherosclerosis, behavior, learning, and longevity.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Rodent experiment shows that neonatal exposure to SSRIs makes persistent changes in the serotonergic transmission of the brain resulting in behavioral changes, which are reversed by treatment with antidepressants.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Human serotonin can also act as a growth factor directly.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Liver damage increases cellular expression of 5-HT2A and 5-HT2B receptors, mediating liver compensatory regrowth (see Liver § Liver regeneration) Serotonin present in the blood then stimulates cellular growth to repair liver damage.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] 5-HT2B receptors also activate osteocytes, which build up bone However, serotonin also inhibits osteoblasts, through 5-HT1B receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin, in addition, evokes endothelial nitric oxide synthase activation and stimulates, through a 5-HT1B receptor-mediated mechanism, the phosphorylation of p44/p42 mitogen-activated protein kinase activation in bovine aortic endothelial cell cultures.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] In blood, serotonin is collected from plasma by platelets, which store it.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] It is thus active wherever platelets bind in damaged tissue, as a vasoconstrictor to stop bleeding, and also as a fibrocyte mitotic (growth factor), to aid healing.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin also regulates white and brown adipose tissue function, and adipocytes are capable of producing 5-HT separately from the gut.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin increases lipogenesis through HTR2A in white adipose tissue, and suppressed thermogenesis in brown adipose tissue via Htr3.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Several classes of drugs target the serotonin system, including some antidepressants, anxiolytics, antipsychotics, analgesics, antimigraine drugs, oxytocics, antiemetics, appetite suppressants, and anticonvulsants, as well as psychedelics and entactogens.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] At rest, serotonin is stored within the vesicles of presynaptic neurons.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] When stimulated by nerve impulses, serotonin is released as a neurotransmitter into the synapse, reversibly binding to the postsynaptic receptor to induce a nerve impulse on the postsynaptic neuron.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin can also bind to auto-receptors on the presynaptic neuron to regulate the synthesis and release of serotonin.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Normally serotonin is taken back into the presynaptic neuron to stop its action, then reused or broken down by monoamine oxidase.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Drugs that alter serotonin levels are used in treating depression, generalized anxiety disorder, and social phobia.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Monoamine oxidase inhibitors (MAOIs) prevent the breakdown of monoamine neurotransmitters (including serotonin), and therefore increase concentrations of the neurotransmitter in the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] MAOI therapy is associated with many adverse drug reactions, and patients are at risk of hypertensive emergency triggered by foods with high tyramine content, and certain drugs.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Some drugs inhibit the re-uptake of serotonin, making it stay in the synaptic cleft longer.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The tricyclic antidepressants (TCAs) inhibit the reuptake of both serotonin and norepinephrine.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The newer selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) have fewer side-effects and fewer interactions with other drugs.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Certain SSRI medications have been shown to lower serotonin levels below the baseline after chronic use, despite initial increases.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The *5-HTTLPR* gene codes for the number of serotonin transporters in the brain, with more serotonin transporters causing decreased duration and magnitude of serotonergic signaling.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The 5-HTTLPR polymorphism (l/l) causing more serotonin transporters to be formed is also found to be more resilient against depression and anxiety.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Besides their use in treating depression and anxiety, certain serotonergic antidepressants are also approved and used to treat fibromyalgia, neuropathic pain, and chronic fatigue syndrome.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Azapirone anxiolytics like buspirone and tandospirone act as serotonin 5-HT1A receptor agonists.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Many antipsychotics bind to and modulate serotonin receptors, including the serotonin 5-HT1A, 5-HT2A, 5-HT2B, 5-HT2C, 5-HT6, and 5-HT7 receptors, among others.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Activation of serotonin 5-HT1A receptors and blockade of serotonin 5-HT2A receptors may contribute to the therapeutic antipsychotic effects of these agents, whereas antagonism of serotonin 5-HT2C receptors has been especially implicated in side effects of antipsychotics.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Antimigraine agents such as the triptans like sumatriptan act as agonists of the serotonin 5-HT1B, 5-HT1D, and/or 5-HT1F receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Earlier antimigraine agents were the ergoline derivatives and ergot-related drugs such as ergotamine, dihydroergotamine, and methysergide, which act as non-selective serotonin receptor agonists.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Certain lysergamides like ergometrine and methylergometrine are used clinically as oxytocic agents.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The oxytocic effects of these drugs are thought to most likely be mediated by agonism of serotonin 5-HT2 receptors in uterine smooth muscle tissue.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Some serotonin 5-HT3 receptor antagonists, such as ondansetron, granisetron, and tropisetron, are important antiemetic agents.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] They are particularly important in treating the nausea and vomiting that occur during anticancer chemotherapy using cytotoxic drugs.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Another application is in the treatment of postoperative nausea and vomiting.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Several of the preceding agents have been withdrawn from the market due to toxicity, such as cardiac fibrosis or pulmonary hypertension.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Although it was previously withdrawn from the market as an appetite suppressant, fenfluramine was reintroduced as an anticonvulsant for treatment of seizures in certain rare forms of epilepsy like Dravet syndrome and Lennox–Gastaut syndrome.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Selective serotonin 5-HT2C receptor agonists, like lorcaserin, bexicaserin, and BMB-101, are also being developed for this use.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] This is evidenced by the fact that serotonin 5-HT2A receptor antagonists and so-called "trip killers" like ketanserin block the hallucinogenic effects of serotonergic psychedelics in humans, among many other findings.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Some serotonergic psychedelics, like psilocin, DMT, and 5-MeO-DMT, are substituted tryptamines and are very similar in chemical structure to serotonin.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin itself, despite acting as a serotonin 5-HT2A receptor agonist, is thought to be non-hallucinogenic.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The hallucinogenic effects of serotonergic psychedelics appear to be mediated by activation of serotonin 5-HT2A receptors expressed in a population of cortical neurons in the medial prefrontal cortex (mPFC).
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] These serotonin 5-HT2A receptors, unlike most serotonin and related receptors, are expressed intracellularly.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] In addition, the neurons containing them lack expression of the serotonin transporter (SERT), which normally transports serotonin from the extracellular space to the intracellular space within neurons.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin itself is too hydrophilic to enter serotonergic neurons without the SERT, and hence these serotonin 5-HT2A receptors are inaccessible to serotonin.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Conversely, serotonergic psychedelics are more lipophilic than serotonin and readily enter these neurons.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] In addition to explaining why serotonin does not show psychedelic effects, these findings may explain why drugs that increase serotonin levels, like selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) and various other types of serotonergic agents, do not produce psychedelic effects.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Artificial expression of the SERT in these medial prefrontal cortex neurons resulted in the serotonin releasing agent *para*-chloroamphetamine (PCA), which does not normally show psychedelic-like effects, being able to produce psychedelic-like effects in animals.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Although serotonin itself is non-hallucinogenic, administration of very high doses of a serotonin precursor, like tryptophan or 5-hydroxytryptophan (5-HTP), or intracerebroventricular injection of high doses of serotonin directly into the brain, can produce psychedelic-like effects in animals.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] These *N*-methyltryptamines are much more lipophilic than serotonin and, in contrast, are able to diffuse into serotonergic neurons and activate intracellular serotonin 5-HT2A receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Another possible metabolite of serotonin with psychedelic-like effects in animals is 5-methoxytryptamine (5-MT).
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] DMT is a naturally occurring endogenous compound in the body.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] In relation to the fact that serotonin itself is unable to activate intracellular serotonin 5-HT2A receptors, it is possible that DMT might be the endogenous ligand of these receptors rather than serotonin.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The entactogen MDMA is a serotonin releasing agent and, while it also possesses other actions such as concomitant release of norepinephrine and dopamine and weak direct agonism of the serotonin 5-HT2 receptors, its serotonin release plays a key role in its unique entactogenic effects.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Entactogens like MDMA should be distinguished from other drugs such as stimulants like amphetamine and psychedelics like LSD, although MDMA itself also has some characteristics of both of these types of agents.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Coadministration of selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs), which block the serotonin transporter (SERT) and prevent MDMA from inducing serotonin release, markedly reduce the subjective effects of MDMA, demonstrating the key role of serotonin in the effects of the drug.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Serotonin releasing agents like MDMA achieve much greater increases in serotonin levels than SSRIs and have far more robust of subjective effects.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Besides MDMA, many other entactogens also exist and are known.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Extremely high levels of serotonin or activation of certain serotonin receptors can cause a condition known as serotonin syndrome, with toxic and potentially fatal effects.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] In practice, such toxic levels are essentially impossible to reach through an overdose of a single antidepressant drug, but require a combination of serotonergic agents, such as an SSRI with a MAOI, which may occur in therapeutic doses.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] However, serotonin syndrome can occur with overdose of certain serotonin receptor agonists, like the NBOMe series of serotonergic psychedelics.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The intensity of the symptoms of serotonin syndrome vary over a wide spectrum, and the milder forms are seen even at nontoxic levels.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] It is estimated that 14% of patients experiencing serotonin syndrome overdose on SSRIs; while the fatality rate is between 2% and 12%.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Some serotonergic agonist drugs cause fibrosis anywhere in the body, particularly the syndrome of retroperitoneal fibrosis, as well as cardiac valve fibrosis.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] In the past, three groups of serotonergic drugs have been epidemiologically linked with these syndromes.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] These are the serotonergic vasoconstrictive antimigraine drugs (ergotamine and methysergide), the serotonergic appetite suppressant drugs (fenfluramine, chlorphentermine, and aminorex), and certain anti-Parkinsonian dopaminergic agonists, which also stimulate serotonergic 5-HT2B receptors.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] These include pergolide and cabergoline, but not the more dopamine-specific lisuride.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] As with fenfluramine, some of these drugs have been withdrawn from the market after groups taking them showed a statistical increase of one or more of the side effects described.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] The drug was declining in use since it was reported in 2003 to be associated with cardiac fibrosis.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Two independent studies published in *The New England Journal of Medicine* in January 2007 implicated pergolide, along with cabergoline, in causing valvular heart disease.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] As a result of this, the FDA removed pergolide from the United States market in March 2007.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] (Since cabergoline is not approved in the United States for Parkinson's Disease, but for hyperprolactinemia, the drug remains on the market.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p01] Treatment for hyperprolactinemia requires lower doses than that for Parkinson's Disease, diminishing the risk of valvular heart disease).
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin is used by a variety of single-cell organisms for various purposes.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] SSRIs have been found to be toxic to algae.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] The gastrointestinal parasite *Entamoeba histolytica* secretes serotonin, causing a sustained secretory diarrhea in some people.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Patients infected with *E. histolytica* have been found to have highly elevated serum serotonin levels, which returned to normal following resolution of the infection.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] *E. histolytica* also responds to the presence of serotonin by becoming more virulent.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] This means serotonin secretion not only serves to increase the spread of entamoebas by giving the host diarrhea but also serves to coordinate their behaviour according to their population density, a phenomenon known as quorum sensing.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Outside the gut of a host, there is nothing that the entamoebas provoke to release serotonin, hence the serotonin concentration is very low.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Low serotonin signals to the entamoebas they are outside a host and they become less virulent to conserve energy.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] When they enter a new host, they multiply in the gut, and become more virulent as the enterochromaffine cells get provoked by them and the serotonin concentration increases.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] In drying seeds, serotonin production is a way to get rid of the buildup of poisonous ammonia.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] The ammonia is collected and placed in the indole part of L-tryptophan, which is then decarboxylated by tryptophan decarboxylase to give tryptamine, which is then hydroxylated by a cytochrome P450 monooxygenase, yielding serotonin.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] However, since serotonin is a major gastrointestinal tract modulator, it may be produced in the fruits of plants as a way of speeding the passage of seeds through the digestive tract, in the same way as many well-known seed and fruit associated laxatives.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin is found in mushrooms, fruits, and vegetables.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] The highest values of 25–400 mg/kg have been found in nuts of the walnut (*Juglans*) and hickory (*Carya*) genera.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin concentrations of 3–30 mg/kg have been found in plantains, pineapples, banana, kiwifruit, plums, and tomatoes.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Moderate levels from 0.1–3 mg/kg have been found in a wide range of tested vegetables.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin is one compound of the poison contained in stinging nettles (*Urtica dioica*), where it causes pain on injection in the same manner as its presence in insect venoms.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] It is also naturally found in *Paramuricea clavata*, or the Red Sea Fan.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin and tryptophan have been found in chocolate with varying cocoa contents.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] The highest serotonin content (2.93 μg/g) was found in chocolate with 85% cocoa, and the highest tryptophan content (13.27–13.34 μg/g) was found in 70–85% cocoa.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] The intermediate in the synthesis from tryptophan to serotonin, 5-hydroxytryptophan, was not found.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Root development in *Arabidopsis thaliana* is stimulated and modulated by serotonin – in various ways at various concentrations.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin serves as a plant defense chemical against fungi.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] When infected with Fusarium crown rot (*Fusarium pseudograminearum*), wheat (*Triticum aestivum*) greatly increases its production of tryptophan to synthesize new serotonin.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] The function of this is poorly understood but wheat also produces serotonin when infected by *Stagonospora nodorum* – in that case to retard spore production.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] The model cereal *Brachypodium distachyon* – used as a research substitute for wheat and other production cereals – also produces serotonin, coumaroyl-serotonin, and feruloyl-serotonin in response to *F. graminearum*.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] This produces a slight antimicrobial effect.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] *B. distachyon* produces more serotonin (and conjugates) in response to deoxynivalenol (DON)-producing *F. graminearum* than non-DON-producing.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] *Solanum lycopersicum* produces many AA conjugates – including several of serotonin – in its leaves, stems, and roots in response to *Ralstonia solanacearum* infection.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin occurs in several hallucinogenic mushrooms of the genus *Panaeolus*.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin functions as a neurotransmitter in the nervous systems of most animals.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] For example, in the roundworm *Caenorhabditis elegans*, which feeds on bacteria, serotonin is released as a signal in response to positive events, such as finding a new source of food or in male animals finding a female with which to mate.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] When a well-fed worm feels bacteria on its cuticle, dopamine is released, which slows it down; if it is starved, serotonin also is released, which slows the animal down further.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] This mechanism increases the amount of time animals spend in the presence of food.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] The released serotonin activates the muscles used for feeding, while octopamine suppresses them.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin diffuses to serotonin-sensitive neurons, which control the animal's perception of nutrient availability.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] If lobsters are injected with serotonin, they behave like dominant individuals whereas octopamine causes subordinate behavior.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] A crayfish that is frightened may flip its tail to flee, and the effect of serotonin on this behavior depends largely on the animal's social status.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin inhibits the fleeing reaction in subordinates, but enhances it in socially dominant or isolated individuals.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] The reason for this is social experience alters the proportion between serotonin receptors (5-HT receptors) that have opposing effects on the fight-or-flight response.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] The effect of 5-HT1 receptors predominates in subordinate animals, while 5-HT2 receptors predominates in dominants.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin is a common component of invertebrate venoms, salivary glands, nervous tissues, and various other tissues, across molluscs, insects, crustaceans, scorpions, various kinds of worms, and jellyfish.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Adult *Rhodnius prolixus* – hematophagous on vertebrates – secrete lipocalins into the wound during feeding.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] In 2003 these lipocalins were demonstrated to sequester serotonin to prevent vasoconstriction (and possibly coagulation) in the host.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin is evolutionarily conserved and appears across the animal kingdom.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] It is seen in insect processes in roles similar to in the human central nervous system, such as memory, appetite, sleep, and behavior.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Some circuits in mushroom bodies are serotonergic.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Locust swarming is initiated *but not maintained* by serotonin, with release being triggered by tactile contact between individuals.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] This transforms social preference from aversion to a gregarious state that enables coherent groups.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Learning in flies and honeybees is affected by the presence of serotonin.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Insect 5-HT receptors have similar sequences to the vertebrate versions, but pharmacological differences have been seen.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Invertebrate drug response has been far less characterized than mammalian pharmacology and the potential for species selective insecticides has been discussed.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Wasps and hornets have serotonin in their venom, which causes pain and inflammation as do scorpions.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] *Pheidole dentata* takes on more and more tasks in the colony as it gets older, which requires it to respond to more and more olfactory cues in the course of performing them.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] This olfactory response broadening was demonstrated to go along with increased serotonin and dopamine, but not octopamine in 2006.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] If flies are fed serotonin, they are more aggressive; flies depleted of serotonin still exhibit aggression, but they do so much less frequently.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] In their crops it plays a vital role in digestive motility produced by contraction.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin that acts on the crop is exogenous to the crop itself and 2012 research suggested that it probably originated in the serotonin neural plexus in the thoracic-abdominal synganglion.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] In 2011 a *Drosophila* serotonergic mushroom body was found to work in concert with *Amnesiac* to form memories.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] In 2007 serotonin was found to promote aggression in *Diptera*, which was counteracted by neuropeptide F – a surprising find given that they both promote courtship, which is usually similar to aggression in most respects.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin, also referred to as 5-hydroxytryptamine (5-HT), is a neurotransmitter most known for its involvement in mood disorders in humans.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] It is also a widely present neuromodulator among vertebrates and invertebrates.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin has been found having associations with many physiological systems such as cardiovascular, thermoregulation, and behavioral functions, including: circadian rhythm, appetite, aggressive and sexual behavior, sensorimotor reactivity and learning, and pain sensitivity.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin's function in neurological systems along with specific behaviors among vertebrates found to be strongly associated with serotonin will be further discussed.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Two relevant case studies are also mentioned regarding serotonin development involving teleost fish and mice.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] In mammals, 5-HT is highly concentrated in the substantia nigra, ventral tegmental area and raphe nuclei.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Lesser concentrated areas include other brain regions and the spinal cord.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] 5-HT neurons are also shown to be highly branched, indicating that they are structurally prominent for influencing multiple areas of the CNS at the same time, although this trend is exclusive solely to mammals.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Vertebrates are multicellular organisms in the phylum Chordata that possess a backbone and a nervous system.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] This includes mammals, fish, reptiles, birds, etc.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] In humans, the nervous system is composed of the central and peripheral nervous system, with little known about the specific mechanisms of neurotransmitters in most other vertebrates.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] However, it is known that while serotonin is involved in stress and behavioral responses, it is also important in cognitive functions.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Brain organization in most vertebrates includes 5-HT cells in the hindbrain.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] In addition to this, 5-HT is often found in other sections of the brain in non-placental vertebrates, including the basal forebrain and pretectum.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Since location of serotonin receptors contribute to behavioral responses, this suggests serotonin is part of specific pathways in non-placental vertebrates that are not present in amniotic organisms.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Teleost fish and mice are organisms most often used to study the connection between serotonin and vertebrate behavior.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Both organisms show similarities in the effect of serotonin on behavior, but differ in the mechanism in which the responses occur.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] There are few studies of serotonin in dogs.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] One study reported serotonin values were higher at dawn than at dusk.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] In another study, serum 5-HT levels did not seem to be associated with dogs' behavioural response to a stressful situation.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Urinary serotonin/creatinine ratio in bitches tended to be higher 4 weeks after surgery.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] In addition, serotonin was positively correlated with both cortisol and progesterone but not with testosterone after ovariohysterectomy.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Like non-placental vertebrates, teleost fish also possess 5-HT cells in other sections of the brain, including the basal forebrain.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] *Danio rerio* (zebra fish) are a species of teleost fish often used for studying serotonin within the brain.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Despite much being unknown about serotonergic systems in vertebrates, the importance in moderating stress and social interaction is known.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] It is hypothesized that AVT and CRF cooperate with serotonin in the hypothalamic-pituitary-interrenal axis.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] These neuropeptides influence the plasticity of the teleost, affecting its ability to change and respond to its environment.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Subordinate fish in social settings show a drastic increase in 5-HT concentrations.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] High levels of 5-HT long term influence the inhibition of aggression in subordinate fish.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Researchers at the Department of Pharmacology and Medical Chemistry used serotonergic drugs on male mice to study the effects of selected drugs on their behavior.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Mice in isolation exhibit increased levels of agonistic behavior towards one another.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Results found that serotonergic drugs reduce aggression in isolated mice while simultaneously increasing social interaction.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Each of the treatments use a different mechanism for targeting aggression, but ultimately all have the same outcome.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] While the study shows that serotonergic drugs successfully target serotonin receptors, it does not show specifics of the mechanisms that affect behavior, as all types of drugs tended to reduce aggression in isolated male mice.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Aggressive mice kept out of isolation may respond differently to changes in serotonin reuptake.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Like in humans, serotonin is involved in regulating behavior in most other vertebrates.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] This includes not only response and social behaviors, but also influencing mood.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Defects in serotonin pathways can lead to intense variations in mood, as well as symptoms of mood disorders, which can be present in more than just humans.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] One of the most researched aspects of social interaction in which serotonin is involved is aggression.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Aggression is regulated by the 5-HT system, as serotonin levels can both induce or inhibit aggressive behaviors, as seen in mice (see section on Mice) and crabs.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] While this is widely accepted, it is unknown if serotonin interacts directly or indirectly with parts of the brain influencing aggression and other behaviors.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Studies of serotonin levels show that they drastically increase and decrease during social interactions, and they generally correlate with inhibiting or inciting aggressive behavior.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] The exact mechanism of serotonin influencing social behaviors is unknown, as pathways in the 5-HT system in various vertebrates can differ greatly.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin is important in environmental response pathways, along with other neurotransmitters.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Specifically, it has been found to be involved in auditory processing in social settings, as primary sensory systems are connected to social interactions.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin is found in the IC structure of the midbrain, which processes specie specific and non-specific social interactions and vocalizations.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] It also receives acoustic projections that convey signals to auditory processing regions.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Research has proposed that serotonin shapes the auditory information being received by the IC and therefore is influential in the responses to auditory stimuli.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] This can influence how an organism responds to the sounds of predatory or other impactful species in their environment, as serotonin uptake can influence aggression or social interaction.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] We can describe mood not as specific to an emotional status, but as associated with a relatively long-lasting emotional state.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Serotonin's association with mood is most known for various forms of depression and bipolar disorders in humans.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Disorders caused by serotonergic activity potentially contribute to the many symptoms of major depression, such as overall mood, activity, suicidal thoughts and sexual and cognitive dysfunction.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRI's) are a class of drugs demonstrated to be an effective treatment in major depressive disorder and are the most prescribed class of antidepressants.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] SSRI's function is to block the reuptake of serotonin, making more serotonin available to absorb by the receiving neuron.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Animals have been studied for decades in order to understand depressive behavior among species.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] One of the most familiar studies, the forced swimming test (FST), was performed to measure potential antidepressant activity.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Rats were placed in an inescapable container of water, at which point time spent immobile and number of active behaviors (such as splashing or climbing) were compared before and after a panel of anti-depressant drugs were administered.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] Antidepressants that selectively inhibit NE reuptake were shown to reduce immobility and selectively increase climbing without affecting swimming.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] However, results of the SSRI's also show reduced immobility but increased swimming without affecting climbing.
[src:neurotransmitters/serotonin-p02] This study demonstrated the importance of behavioral tests for antidepressants, as they can detect drugs with an effect on core behavior along with behavioral components of species.
